18Jb 1:1 There was a man in the country of Uz named Job. He was a man of perfect integrity, who feared God and turned away from evil.
18Jb 1:2 He had seven sons and three daughters.
18Jb 1:3 His estate included 7,000 sheep, 3,000 camels, 500 yoke of oxen, 500 female donkeys, and a very large number of servants. Job was the greatest man among all the people of the east.
18Jb 1:4 His sons used to have banquets, each at his house in turn. They would send an invitation to their three sisters to eat and drink with them.
18Jb 1:5 Whenever a round of banqueting was over, Job would send [for his children] and purify them, rising early in the morning to offer burnt offerings for all of them. For Job thought: Perhaps my children have sinned, having cursed God in their hearts. This was Job's regular practice.
18Jb 1:6 One day the sons of God came to present themselves before the LORD, and Satan also came with them.
18Jb 1:7 The LORD asked Satan, "Where have you come from?" "From roaming through the earth," Satan answered Him, "and walking around on it."
18Jb 1:8 Then the LORD said to Satan, "Have you considered My servant Job? No one else on earth is like him, a man of perfect integrity, who fears God and turns away from evil."
18Jb 1:9 Satan answered the LORD, "Does Job fear God for nothing?
18Jb 1:10 Haven't You placed a hedge around him, his household, and everything he owns? You have blessed the work of his hands, and his possessions are spread out in the land.
18Jb 1:11 But stretch out Your hand and strike everything he owns, and he will surely curse You to Your face."
18Jb 1:12 "Very well," the LORD told Satan, "everything he owns is in your power. However, you must not lay a hand on Job [himself]." So Satan went out from the Lord's presence.
18Jb 1:13 One day when Job's sons and daughters were eating and drinking wine in their oldest brother's house,
18Jb 1:14 a messenger came to Job and reported: "While the oxen were plowing and the donkeys grazing nearby,
18Jb 1:15 the Sabeans swooped down and took them away. They struck down the servants with the sword, and I alone have escaped to tell you!"
18Jb 1:16 He was still speaking when another [messenger] came and reported: "A lightning storm struck from heaven. It burned up the sheep and the servants, and devoured them, and I alone have escaped to tell you!"
18Jb 1:17 That messenger was still speaking when [yet] another came and reported: "The Chaldeans formed three bands, made a raid on the camels, and took them away. They struck down the servants with the sword, and I alone have escaped to tell you!"
18Jb 1:18 He was still speaking when another [messenger] came and reported: "Your sons and daughters were eating and drinking wine in their oldest brother's house.
18Jb 1:19 Suddenly a powerful wind swept in from the desert and struck the four corners of the house. It collapsed on the young people so that they died, and I alone have escaped to tell you!"
18Jb 1:20 Then Job stood up, tore his robe and shaved his head. He fell to the ground and worshiped,
18Jb 1:21 saying: Naked I came from my mother's womb, and naked I will leave this life. The LORD gives, and the LORD takes away. Praise the name of the LORD.
18Jb 1:22 Throughout all this Job did not sin or blame God for anything.
18Jb 2:1 One day the sons of God came again to present themselves before the LORD, and Satan also came with them to present himself before the LORD.
18Jb 2:2 The LORD asked Satan, "Where have you come from?" "From roaming through the earth," Satan answered Him, "and walking around on it."
18Jb 2:3 Then the LORD said to Satan, "Have you considered My servant Job? No one else on earth is like him, a man of perfect integrity, who fears God and turns away from evil. He still retains his integrity, even though you incited Me against him, to destroy him without just cause."
18Jb 2:4 "Skin for skin!" Satan answered the LORD. "A man will give up everything he owns in exchange for his life.
18Jb 2:5 But stretch out Your hand and strike his flesh and bones, and he will surely curse You to Your face."
18Jb 2:6 "Very well," the LORD told Satan, "he is in your power; only spare his life."
18Jb 2:7 So Satan left the LORD's presence and infected Job with incurable boils from the sole of his foot to the top of his head.
18Jb 2:8 Then Job took a piece of broken pottery to scrape himself while he sat among the ashes.
18Jb 2:9 His wife said to him, "Do you still retain your integrity? Curse God and die!"
18Jb 2:10 "You speak as a foolish woman speaks," he told her. "Should we accept only good from God and not adversity?" Throughout all this Job did not sin in what he said.
18Jb 2:11 Now when Job's three friends-- Eliphaz the Temanite, Bildad the Shuhite, and Zophar the Naamathite-- heard about all this adversity that had happened to him, each of them came from his home. They met together to go and offer sympathy and comfort to him.
18Jb 2:12 When they looked from a distance, they could [barely] recognize him. They wept aloud, and each man tore his robe and threw dust into the air and on his head.
18Jb 2:13 Then they sat on the ground with him seven days and nights, but no one spoke a word to him because they saw that his suffering was very intense.
18Jb 3:1 After this Job began to speak and cursed the day he was born.
18Jb 3:2 He said:
18Jb 3:3 May the day I was born perish, and the night when they said, "A boy is conceived."
18Jb 3:4 If only that day had turned to darkness! May God above not care about it, or light shine on it.
18Jb 3:5 May darkness and gloom reclaim it, and a cloud settle over it. May an eclipse of the sun terrify it.
18Jb 3:6 If only darkness had taken that night away! May it not appear among the days of the year or be listed in the calendar.
18Jb 3:7 Yes, may that night be barren; may no joyful shout be heard in it.
18Jb 3:8 Let those who curse [certain] days cast a spell on it, those who are skilled in rousing Leviathan.
18Jb 3:9 May its morning stars grow dark. May it wait for daylight but have none; may it not see the breaking of dawn.
18Jb 3:10 For that night did not shut the doors of my [mother's] womb, and hide sorrow from my eyes.
18Jb 3:11 Why was I not stillborn; [why] didn't I die as I came from the womb?
18Jb 3:12 Why did the knees receive me, and why were there breasts for me to nurse?
18Jb 3:13 For then I would have laid down in peace; I would be asleep. Then I would be at rest
18Jb 3:14 with the kings and counselors of the earth, who rebuilt ruined cities for themselves,
18Jb 3:15 or with princes who had gold, who filled their houses with silver.
18Jb 3:16 Or [why] was I not hidden like a miscarried child, like infants who never see daylight?
18Jb 3:17 There the wicked cease to make trouble, and there the weary find rest.
18Jb 3:18 The captives are completely at ease; they do not hear the voice of [their] oppressor.
18Jb 3:19 Both the small and the great are there, and the slave is set free from his master.
18Jb 3:20 Why is light given to one burdened with grief, and life to those whose existence is bitter,
18Jb 3:21 who wait for death, but it does not come, and search for it more than for hidden treasure,
18Jb 3:22 who are filled with much joy and are glad when they reach the grave?
18Jb 3:23 [Why is life given] to a man whose path is hidden, whom God has hedged in?
18Jb 3:24 I sigh when food is [put] before me, and my groans pour out like water.
18Jb 3:25 For the thing I feared has overtaken me, and what I dreaded has happened to me.
18Jb 3:26 I cannot relax or be still; I have no rest, for trouble comes.
18Jb 4:1 Then Eliphaz the Temanite replied:
18Jb 4:2 Should anyone try to speak with you when you are exhausted? Yet who can keep from speaking?
18Jb 4:3 Look! You have instructed many and have strengthened weak hands.
18Jb 4:4 Your words have steadied the one who was stumbling, and braced the knees that were buckling.
18Jb 4:5 But now that this has happened to you, you have become exhausted. It strikes you, and you are dismayed.
18Jb 4:6 Isn't your piety your confidence, and the integrity of your life your hope?
18Jb 4:7 Consider: who has perished when he was innocent? Where have the honest been destroyed?
18Jb 4:8 In my experience, those who plow injustice and those who sow trouble reap the same.
18Jb 4:9 They perish at a [single] blast from God and come to an end by the breath of His nostrils.
18Jb 4:10 The lion may roar and the fierce lion growl, but the fangs of young lions are broken.
18Jb 4:11 The strong lion dies if [it catches] no prey, and the cubs of the lioness are scattered.
18Jb 4:12 A word was brought to me in secret; my ears caught a whisper of it.
18Jb 4:13 Among unsettling thoughts from visions in the night, when deep sleep descends on men,
18Jb 4:14 fear and trembling came over me and made all my bones shake.
18Jb 4:15 A wind passed by me, and I shuddered with fear.
18Jb 4:16 [A figure] stood there, but I could not recognize its appearance; a form loomed before my eyes. I heard a quiet voice:
18Jb 4:17 "Can a person be more righteous than God, or a man more pure than his Maker?"
18Jb 4:18 If God puts no trust in His servants and He charges His angels with foolishness,
18Jb 4:19 how much more those who dwell in clay houses, whose foundation is in the dust, who are crushed like a moth!
18Jb 4:20 They are smashed to pieces from dawn to dusk; they perish forever while no one notices.
18Jb 4:21 Are their tent cords not pulled up? They die without wisdom.
18Jb 5:1 Call out if you please. Will anyone answer you? Which of the holy ones will you turn to?
18Jb 5:2 For anger kills a fool, and jealousy slays the gullible.
18Jb 5:3 I have seen a fool taking root, but I immediately pronounced a curse on his home.
18Jb 5:4 His children are far from safety. They are crushed at the [city] gate, with no one to defend [them].
18Jb 5:5 The hungry consume his harvest, even taking it out of the thorns. The thirsty pant for his children's wealth.
18Jb 5:6 For distress does not grow out of the soil, and trouble does not sprout from the ground.
18Jb 5:7 But mankind is born for trouble as surely as sparks fly upward.
18Jb 5:8 However, if I were you, I would appeal to God and would present my case to Him.
18Jb 5:9 He does great and unsearchable things, wonders without number.
18Jb 5:10 He gives rain to the earth and sends water to the fields.
18Jb 5:11 He sets the lowly on high, and mourners are lifted to safety.
18Jb 5:12 He frustrates the schemes of the crafty so that they achieve no success.
18Jb 5:13 He traps the wise in their craftiness so that the plans of the deceptive are quickly brought to an end.
18Jb 5:14 They encounter darkness by day, and they grope at noon as if it were night.
18Jb 5:15 He saves the needy from their sharp words and from the clutches of the powerful.
18Jb 5:16 So the poor have hope, and injustice shuts its mouth.
18Jb 5:17 See how happy the man is God corrects; so do not reject the discipline of the Almighty.
18Jb 5:18 For He crushes but also binds up; He strikes, but His hands also heal.
18Jb 5:19 He will rescue you from six calamities; no harm will touch you in seven.
18Jb 5:20 In famine He will redeem you from death, and in battle, from the power of the sword.
18Jb 5:21 You will be safe from slander and not fear destruction when it comes.
18Jb 5:22 You will laugh at destruction and hunger and not fear the animals of the earth.
18Jb 5:23 For you will have a covenant with the stones of the field, and the wild animals will be at peace with you.
18Jb 5:24 You will know that your tent is secure, and nothing will be missing when you inspect your home.
18Jb 5:25 You will also know that your offspring will be many and your descendants like the grass of the earth.
18Jb 5:26 You will approach the grave in full vigor, as a stack of sheaves is gathered in its season.
18Jb 5:27 We have investigated this, and it is true! Hear it and understand [it] for yourself.
18Jb 6:1 Then Job answered:
18Jb 6:2 If only my grief could be weighed and my devastation placed with it on a scale.
18Jb 6:3 For then it would outweigh the sand of the seas! That is why my words are rash.
18Jb 6:4 Surely the arrows of the Almighty have pierced me; my spirit drinks their poison. God's terrors are arrayed against me.
18Jb 6:5 Does a wild donkey bray over fresh grass or an ox low over its fodder?
18Jb 6:6 Is bland food eaten without salt? Is there flavor in an egg white?
18Jb 6:7 I refuse to touch [them]; they are like contaminated food.
18Jb 6:8 If only my request would be granted and God would provide what I hope for:
18Jb 6:9 that He would decide to crush me, to unleash His power and cut me off!
18Jb 6:10 It would still bring me comfort, and I would leap for joy in unrelenting pain that I have not denied the words of the Holy One.
18Jb 6:11 What strength do I have that I should continue to hope? What is my future, that I should be patient?
18Jb 6:12 Is my strength that of stone, or my flesh made of bronze?
18Jb 6:13 Since I cannot help myself, [the hope for] success has been banished from me.
18Jb 6:14 A despairing man should receive loyalty from his friends, even if he abandons the fear of the Almighty.
18Jb 6:15 My brothers are as treacherous as a wadi, as seasonal streams that overflow
18Jb 6:16 and become darkened because of ice, and the snow melts into them.
18Jb 6:17 The wadis evaporate in warm weather; they disappear from their channels in hot weather.
18Jb 6:18 Caravans turn away from their routes, go up into the desert, and perish.
18Jb 6:19 The caravans of Tema look [for these streams]. The traveling merchants of Sheba hope for them.
18Jb 6:20 They are ashamed because they had been confident [of finding water]. When they arrive there, they are frustrated.
18Jb 6:21 So [this] is what you have now become [to me]. When you see something dreadful, you are afraid.
18Jb 6:22 Have I ever said: Give me [something] or Pay a bribe for me from your wealth
18Jb 6:23 or Deliver me from the enemy's power or Redeem me from the grasp of the ruthless?
18Jb 6:24 Teach me, and I will be silent. Help me understand what I did wrong.
18Jb 6:25 How painful honest words can be! But what does your rebuke prove?
18Jb 6:26 Do you think that you can disprove [my] words or that a despairing man's words are [mere] wind?
18Jb 6:27 No doubt you would cast [lots] for a fatherless child and negotiate a price to [sell] your friend.
18Jb 6:28 But now, please look at me; would I lie to your face?
18Jb 6:29 Reconsider; don't be unjust. Reconsider; my righteousness is still the issue.
18Jb 6:30 Am I lying, or can I not recognize lies?
18Jb 7:1 Isn't mankind consigned to forced labor on earth? Are not his days like those of a hired hand?
18Jb 7:2 Like a slave he longs for shade; like a hired man he waits for his pay.
18Jb 7:3 So I have been made to inherit months of futility, and troubled nights have been assigned to me.
18Jb 7:4 When I lie down I think: When will I get up? But the evening drags on endlessly, and I toss and turn until dawn.
18Jb 7:5 My flesh is clothed with maggots and encrusted with dirt. My skin forms scabs and then oozes.
18Jb 7:6 My days pass more swiftly than a weaver's shuttle; they come to an end without hope.
18Jb 7:7 Remember that my life is [but] a breath. My eye will never again see anything good.
18Jb 7:8 The eye of anyone who looks on me will no longer see me. Your eyes will look for me, but I will be gone.
18Jb 7:9 As a cloud fades away and vanishes, so the one who goes down to Sheol will never rise again.
18Jb 7:10 He will never return to his house; his hometown will no longer remember him.
18Jb 7:11 Therefore I will not restrain my mouth. I will speak in the anguish of my spirit; I will complain in the bitterness of my soul.
18Jb 7:12 Am I the sea or a sea monster, that You keep me under guard?
18Jb 7:13 When I say: My bed will comfort me, and my couch will ease my complaint,
18Jb 7:14 then You frighten me with dreams, and terrify me with visions,
18Jb 7:15 so that I prefer strangling, death rather than life in this body.
18Jb 7:16 I give up! I will not live forever. Leave me alone, for my days are a breath.
18Jb 7:17 What is man, that You think so highly of him and pay so much attention to him?
18Jb 7:18 You inspect him every morning, and put him to the test every moment.
18Jb 7:19 Will You ever look away from me, or leave me alone until I swallow my saliva?
18Jb 7:20 [If] I have sinned, what have I done to You, Watcher of mankind? Why have You made me Your target, so that I have become a burden to You?
18Jb 7:21 Why not forgive my sin and pardon my transgression? For soon I will lie down in the grave. You will eagerly seek me, but I will be gone.
18Jb 8:1 Then Bildad the Shuhite replied:
18Jb 8:2 How long will you go on saying these things? Your words are a blast of wind.
18Jb 8:3 Does God pervert justice? Does the Almighty pervert what is right?
18Jb 8:4 Since your children sinned against Him, He gave them over to their rebellion.
18Jb 8:5 But if you earnestly seek God and ask the Almighty for mercy,
18Jb 8:6 if you are pure and upright, then He will move even now on your behalf and restore the home where your righteousness dwells.
18Jb 8:7 Then, even if your beginnings were modest, your final days will be full of prosperity.
18Jb 8:8 For ask the previous generation, and pay attention to what their fathers discovered,
18Jb 8:9 since we were [born only] yesterday and know nothing. Our days on earth are but a shadow.
18Jb 8:10 Will they not teach you and tell you and speak from their understanding?
18Jb 8:11 Does papyrus grow where there is no marsh? Do reeds flourish without water?
18Jb 8:12 While still uncut shoots, they would dry up quicker than any [other] plant.
18Jb 8:13 Such is the destiny of all who forget God; the hope of the godless will perish.
18Jb 8:14 His source of confidence is fragile; what he trusts in is a spider's web.
18Jb 8:15 He leans on his web, but it doesn't stand firm. He grabs it, but it does not hold up.
18Jb 8:16 He is an amply watered plant in the sunshine; his shoots spread out over his garden.
18Jb 8:17 His roots are intertwined around a pile of rocks. He looks for a home among the stones.
18Jb 8:18 If he is uprooted from his place, it will deny [knowing] him, saying, "I never saw you."
18Jb 8:19 Surely this is the joy of his way of life; yet others will sprout from the dust.
18Jb 8:20 Look, God does not reject a person of integrity, and He will not support evildoers.
18Jb 8:21 He will yet fill your mouth with laughter and your lips with a shout of joy.
18Jb 8:22 Your enemies will be clothed with shame; the tent of the wicked will exist no longer.
18Jb 9:1 Then Job answered:
18Jb 9:2 Yes, I know what you've said is true, but how can a person be justified before God?
18Jb 9:3 If one wanted to take Him to court, he could not answer God once in a thousand [times].
18Jb 9:4 God is wise and all-powerful. Who has opposed Him and come out unharmed?
18Jb 9:5 He removes mountains without their knowledge, overturning them in His anger.
18Jb 9:6 He shakes the earth from its place so that its pillars tremble.
18Jb 9:7 He commands the sun not to shine and seals off the stars.
18Jb 9:8 He alone stretches out the heavens and treads on the waves of the sea.
18Jb 9:9 He makes [the stars]: the Bear, Orion, the Pleiades, and the constellations of the southern sky.
18Jb 9:10 He performs great and unsearchable things, wonders without number.
18Jb 9:11 If He passes by me, I wouldn't see Him; [if] He goes right by, I wouldn't recognize Him.
18Jb 9:12 If He snatches [something], who can stop Him? Who can ask Him, "What are You doing?"
18Jb 9:13 God does not hold back His anger; Rahab's assistants cringe in fear beneath Him!
18Jb 9:14 How then can I answer Him or choose my arguments against Him?
18Jb 9:15 Even if I were in the right, I could not answer. I could only beg my judge for mercy.
18Jb 9:16 If I summoned [Him] and He answered me, I do not believe He would pay attention to what I said.
18Jb 9:17 He batters me with a whirlwind and multiplies my wounds without cause.
18Jb 9:18 He doesn't let me catch my breath but soaks me with bitter experiences.
18Jb 9:19 If it is a matter of strength, look, He is the Mighty One! If it is a matter of justice, who can summon Him?
18Jb 9:20 Even if I were in the right, my own mouth would condemn me; if I were blameless, my mouth would declare me guilty.
18Jb 9:21 Though I am blameless, I no longer care about myself; I renounce my life.
18Jb 9:22 It is all the same. Therefore I say, "He destroys both the blameless and the wicked."
18Jb 9:23 When disaster brings sudden death, He mocks the despair of the innocent.
18Jb 9:24 The earth is handed over to the wicked; He blindfolds its judges. If it isn't He, then who is it?
18Jb 9:25 My days fly by faster than a runner; they flee without seeing any good.
18Jb 9:26 They sweep by like boats made of papyrus, like an eagle swooping down on [its] prey.
18Jb 9:27 If I said, "I will forget my complaint, change my expression, and smile,"
18Jb 9:28 I would still live in terror of all my pains. I know You will not acquit me.
18Jb 9:29 Since I will be found guilty, why should I labor in vain?
18Jb 9:30 If I wash myself with snow, and cleanse my hands with lye,
18Jb 9:31 then You dip me in a pit [of mud], and my own clothes despise me!
18Jb 9:32 For He is not a man like me, that I can answer Him, that we can take each other to court.
18Jb 9:33 There is no one to judge between us, to lay his hand on both of us.
18Jb 9:34 Let Him take His rod away from me so His terror will no longer frighten me.
18Jb 9:35 Then I would speak and not fear Him. But that is not the case; I am on my own.
18Jb 10:1 I am disgusted with my life. I will express my complaint and speak in the bitterness of my soul.
18Jb 10:2 I will say to God: Do not declare me guilty! Let me know why You prosecute me.
18Jb 10:3 Is it good for You to oppress, to reject the work of Your hands, and favor the plans of the wicked?
18Jb 10:4 Do You have eyes of flesh, or do You see as a human sees?
18Jb 10:5 Are Your days like those of a human, or Your years like those of a man,
18Jb 10:6 that You look for my wrongdoing and search for my sin,
18Jb 10:7 even though You know that I am not wicked and that there is no one who can deliver from Your hand?
18Jb 10:8 Your hands shaped me and formed me. Will You now turn around and destroy me?
18Jb 10:9 Please remember that You formed me like clay. Will You now return me to dust?
18Jb 10:10 Did You not pour me out like milk and curdle me like cheese?
18Jb 10:11 You clothed me with skin and flesh, and wove me together with bones and tendons.
18Jb 10:12 You gave me life and faithful love, and Your care has guarded my life.
18Jb 10:13 Yet You concealed these [thoughts] in Your heart; I know that this was Your hidden plan:
18Jb 10:14 if I sin, You would notice, and would not acquit me of my wrongdoing.
18Jb 10:15 If I am wicked, woe to me! And even if I am righteous, I cannot lift up my head. I am filled with shame and aware of my affliction.
18Jb 10:16 If I am proud, You hunt me like a lion and again display Your miraculous power against me.
18Jb 10:17 You produce new witnesses against me and multiply Your anger toward me. Hardships assault me, wave after wave.
18Jb 10:18 Why did You bring me out of the womb? I should have died and never been seen.
18Jb 10:19 I wish I had never existed but had been carried from the womb to the grave.
18Jb 10:20 Are my days not few? Stop [it]! Leave me alone, so that I can smile a little
18Jb 10:21 before I go to a land of darkness and gloom, never to return.
18Jb 10:22 [It is] a land of blackness like the deepest darkness, gloomy and chaotic, where even the light is like the darkness.
18Jb 11:1 Then Zophar the Naamathite replied:
18Jb 11:2 Should this stream of words go unanswered and such a talker be acquitted?
18Jb 11:3 Should your babbling put others to silence, so that you can keep on ridiculing with no one to humiliate you?
18Jb 11:4 You have said, "My teaching is sound, and I am pure in Your sight."
18Jb 11:5 But if only God would speak and declare His case against you,
18Jb 11:6 He would show you the secrets of wisdom, for true wisdom has two sides. Know then that God has chosen to overlook some of your sin.
18Jb 11:7 Can you fathom the depths of God or discover the limits of the Almighty?
18Jb 11:8 [They are] higher than the heavens-- what can you do? [They are] deeper than Sheol-- what can you know?
18Jb 11:9 Their measure is longer than the earth and wider than the sea.
18Jb 11:10 If He passes by and throws [someone] in prison or convenes a court, who can stop Him?
18Jb 11:11 Surely He knows which people are worthless. If He sees iniquity, will He not take note [of it]?
18Jb 11:12 But a stupid man will gain understanding as soon as a wild donkey is born a man!
18Jb 11:13 As for you, if you redirect your heart and lift up your hands to Him [in prayer]--
18Jb 11:14 if there is iniquity in your hand, remove it, and don't allow injustice to dwell in your tents--
18Jb 11:15 then you will hold your head high, free from fault. You will be firmly established and unafraid.
18Jb 11:16 For you will forget your suffering, recalling [it only] as waters that have flowed by.
18Jb 11:17 [Your] life will be brighter than noonday; [its] darkness will be like the morning.
18Jb 11:18 You will be confident, because there is hope. You will look carefully about and lie down in safety.
18Jb 11:19 You will lie down without fear, and many will seek your favor.
18Jb 11:20 But the sight of the wicked will fail. Their way of escape will be cut off, and their [only] hope will be to die.
18Jb 12:1 Then Job answered:
18Jb 12:2 No doubt you are the people, and wisdom will die with you!
18Jb 12:3 But I also have a mind; I am not inferior to you. Who doesn't know the things you are talking about?
18Jb 12:4 I am a laughingstock to my friends, by calling on God, who answers me. The righteous and upright man is a laughingstock.
18Jb 12:5 The one who is at ease holds calamity in contempt [and thinks] it is prepared for those whose feet are slipping.
18Jb 12:6 The tents of robbers are safe, and those who provoke God are secure; God's power provides this.
18Jb 12:7 But ask the animals, and they will instruct you; [ask] the birds of the sky, and they will tell you.
18Jb 12:8 Or speak to the earth, and it will instruct you; let the fish of the sea inform you.
18Jb 12:9 Which of all these does not know that the hand of the LORD has done this?
18Jb 12:10 The life of every living thing is in His hand, as well as the breath of all mankind.
18Jb 12:11 Doesn't the ear test words as the palate tastes food?
18Jb 12:12 Wisdom is found with the elderly, and understanding comes with long life.
18Jb 12:13 Wisdom and strength belong to God; counsel and understanding are His.
18Jb 12:14 Whatever He tears down cannot be rebuilt; whoever He imprisons cannot be released.
18Jb 12:15 When He withholds the waters, everything dries up, and when He releases them, they destroy the land.
18Jb 12:16 True wisdom and power belong to Him. The deceived and the deceiver are His.
18Jb 12:17 He leads counselors away barefoot and makes judges go mad.
18Jb 12:18 He releases the bonds put on by kings and ties a cloth around their waists.
18Jb 12:19 He leads priests away barefoot and overthrows established leaders.
18Jb 12:20 He deprives trusted advisers of speech and takes away the elders' good judgment.
18Jb 12:21 He pours out contempt on nobles and disarms the strong.
18Jb 12:22 He reveals mysteries from the darkness and brings the deepest darkness into the light.
18Jb 12:23 He makes nations great, then destroys them; He enlarges nations, then leads them away.
18Jb 12:24 He deprives the world's leaders of reason, and makes them wander in a trackless wasteland.
18Jb 12:25 They grope around in darkness without light; He makes them stagger like drunken men.
18Jb 13:1 Look, my eyes have seen all this; my ears have heard and understood it.
18Jb 13:2 Everything you know, I also know; I am not inferior to you.
18Jb 13:3 Yet I prefer to speak to the Almighty and argue my case before God.
18Jb 13:4 But you coat [the truth] with lies; you are all worthless doctors.
18Jb 13:5 If only you would shut up and let that be your wisdom!
18Jb 13:6 Hear now my argument, and listen to my defense.
18Jb 13:7 Would you testify unjustly on God's behalf or speak deceitfully for Him?
18Jb 13:8 Would you show partiality to Him or argue the case in His defense?
18Jb 13:9 Would it go well if He examined you? Could you deceive Him as you would deceive a man?
18Jb 13:10 Surely He would rebuke you if you secretly showed partiality.
18Jb 13:11 Would God's majesty not terrify you? Would His dread not fall on you?
18Jb 13:12 Your memorable sayings are proverbs of ash; your defenses are made of clay.
18Jb 13:13 Be quiet, and I will speak. Let whatever comes happen to me.
18Jb 13:14 Why do I put myself at risk and take my life in my own hands?
18Jb 13:15 Even if He kills me, I will hope in Him. I will still defend my ways before Him.
18Jb 13:16 Yes, this will result in my deliverance, for no godless person can appear before Him.
18Jb 13:17 Pay close attention to my words; let my declaration [ring] in your ears.
18Jb 13:18 Now then, I have prepared [my] case; I know that I am right.
18Jb 13:19 Can anyone indict me? If so, I will be silent and die.
18Jb 13:20 Only grant [these] two things to me, [God], so that I will not have to hide from Your presence:
18Jb 13:21 remove Your hand from me, and do not let Your terror frighten me.
18Jb 13:22 Then call, and I will answer, or I will speak, and You can respond to me.
18Jb 13:23 How many iniquities and sins have I committed? Reveal to me my transgression and sin.
18Jb 13:24 Why do You hide Your face and consider me Your enemy?
18Jb 13:25 Will You frighten a wind-driven leaf? Will You chase after dry straw?
18Jb 13:26 For You record bitter accusations against me and make me inherit the iniquities of my youth.
18Jb 13:27 You put my feet in the stocks and stand watch over all my paths, setting a limit for the soles of my feet.
18Jb 13:28 Man wears out like something rotten, like a moth-eaten garment.
18Jb 14:1 Man born of woman is short of days and full of trouble.
18Jb 14:2 He blossoms like a flower, then withers; he flees like a shadow and does not last.
18Jb 14:3 Do You really take notice of one like this? Will You bring me into judgment against You?
18Jb 14:4 Who can produce something pure from what is impure? No one!
18Jb 14:5 Since man's days are determined and the number of his months depends on You, and [since] You have set limits he cannot pass,
18Jb 14:6 look away from him and let him rest so that he can enjoy his day like a hired hand.
18Jb 14:7 There is hope for a tree: If it is cut down, it will sprout again, and its shoots will not die.
18Jb 14:8 If its roots grow old in the ground and its stump starts to die in the soil,
18Jb 14:9 the smell of water makes it thrive and produce twigs like a sapling.
18Jb 14:10 But a man dies and fades away; he breathes his last-- where is he?
18Jb 14:11 As water disappears from the sea and a wadi becomes parched and dry,
18Jb 14:12 so man lies down never to rise again. They will not wake up until the heavens are no more; they will not stir from their sleep.
18Jb 14:13 If only You would hide me in Sheol and conceal me until Your anger passes, that You would appoint a time for me and then remember me.
18Jb 14:14 When a man dies, will he come back to life? [If so,] I would wait all the days of my struggle until my relief comes.
18Jb 14:15 You would call, and I would answer You. You would long for the work of Your hands.
18Jb 14:16 For then You would count my steps but would not take note of my sin.
18Jb 14:17 My rebellion would be sealed up in a bag, and You would cover over my iniquity.
18Jb 14:18 But as a mountain collapses and crumbles and a rock is dislodged from its place,
18Jb 14:19 as water wears away stones and torrents wash away the soil from the land, so You destroy a man's hope.
18Jb 14:20 You completely overpower him, and he passes on; You change his appearance and send him away.
18Jb 14:21 If his sons receive honor, he does not know it; if they become insignificant, he is unaware of it.
18Jb 14:22 He feels only the pain of his own body and mourns only for himself.
18Jb 15:1 Then Eliphaz the Temanite replied:
18Jb 15:2 Does a wise man answer with empty counsel or fill himself with the hot east wind?
18Jb 15:3 Should he argue with useless talk or with words that serve no good purpose?
18Jb 15:4 But you even undermine the fear [of God] and hinder meditation before Him.
18Jb 15:5 Your iniquity teaches you what to say, and you choose the language of the crafty.
18Jb 15:6 Your own mouth condemns you, not I; your own lips testify against you.
18Jb 15:7 Were you the first person ever born, or were you brought forth before the hills?
18Jb 15:8 Do you listen in on the council of God, or have a monopoly on wisdom?
18Jb 15:9 What do you know that we don't? [What] do you understand that is not [clear] to us?
18Jb 15:10 Both the gray-haired and the elderly are with us, men older than your father.
18Jb 15:11 Are God's consolations not enough for you, even the words that [deal] gently with you?
18Jb 15:12 Why has your heart misled you, and why do your eyes flash
18Jb 15:13 as you turn your anger against God and allow such words to leave your mouth?
18Jb 15:14 What is man, that he should be pure, or one born of woman, that he should be righteous?
18Jb 15:15 If God puts no trust in His holy ones and the heavens are not pure in His sight,
18Jb 15:16 how much less one who is revolting and corrupt, who drinks injustice like water?
18Jb 15:17 Listen to me and I will inform you. I will describe what I have seen,
18Jb 15:18 what was declared by wise men and was not suppressed by their ancestors,
18Jb 15:19 the land was given to them alone when no foreigner passed among them.
18Jb 15:20 A wicked man writhes in pain all his days; few years are stored up for the ruthless.
18Jb 15:21 Dreadful sounds fill his ears; when he is at peace, a robber attacks him.
18Jb 15:22 He doesn't believe he will return from darkness; he is destined for the sword.
18Jb 15:23 He wanders about for food, [saying,] "Where is it?" He knows the day of darkness is at hand.
18Jb 15:24 Trouble and distress terrify him, overwhelming him like a king prepared for battle.
18Jb 15:25 For he has stretched out his hand against God and has arrogantly opposed the Almighty.
18Jb 15:26 He rushes headlong at Him with his thick, studded shields.
18Jb 15:27 Though his face is covered with fat and his waistline bulges with it,
18Jb 15:28 he will dwell in ruined cities, in abandoned houses destined to become piles of rubble.
18Jb 15:29 He will no longer be rich; his wealth will not endure. His possessions will not spread over the land.
18Jb 15:30 He will not escape from the darkness; flames will wither his shoots, and he will depart by the breath of God's mouth.
18Jb 15:31 Let him not put trust in worthless things, being led astray, for what he gets in exchange will prove worthless.
18Jb 15:32 It will be accomplished before his time, and his branch will not flourish.
18Jb 15:33 He will be like a vine that drops its unripe grapes and like an olive tree that sheds its blossoms.
18Jb 15:34 For the company of the godless will be barren, and fire will consume the tents of those who offer bribes.
18Jb 15:35 They conceive trouble and give birth to evil; their womb prepares deception.
18Jb 16:1 Then Job answered:
18Jb 16:2 I have heard many things like these. You are all miserable comforters.
18Jb 16:3 Is there [no] end to your empty words? What provokes you that you continue testifying?
18Jb 16:4 If you were in my place I could also talk like you. I could string words together against you and shake my head at you, [but I wouldn't].
18Jb 16:5 I would encourage you with my mouth, and the consolation from my lips would bring relief.
18Jb 16:6 Even if I speak, my suffering is not relieved, and if I hold back, what have I lost?
18Jb 16:7 Surely He has now exhausted me. You have devastated my entire family.
18Jb 16:8 You have shriveled me up-- it has become a witness; My frailty rises up against me and testifies to my face.
18Jb 16:9 His anger tears [at me], and He harasses me. He gnashes His teeth at me. My enemy pierces me with His eyes.
18Jb 16:10 They open their mouths against me and strike my cheeks with contempt; they join themselves together against me.
18Jb 16:11 God hands me over to unjust men; He throws me into the hands of the wicked.
18Jb 16:12 I was at ease, but He shattered me; He seized [me] by the scruff of the neck and smashed me to pieces. He set me up as His target;
18Jb 16:13 His archers surround me. He pierces my kidneys without mercy and pours my bile on the ground.
18Jb 16:14 He breaks through my defenses again and again; He charges at me like a warrior.
18Jb 16:15 I have sewn sackcloth over my skin; I have buried my strength in the dust.
18Jb 16:16 My face has grown red with weeping, and the shadow of death covers my eyes,
18Jb 16:17 although my hands are free from violence and my prayer is pure.
18Jb 16:18 Earth, do not cover my blood; may my cry for help find no resting place.
18Jb 16:19 Even now my witness is in heaven, and my advocate is in the heights!
18Jb 16:20 My friends scoff at me as I weep before God.
18Jb 16:21 I wish that someone might arbitrate between a man and God just as a man [pleads] for his friend.
18Jb 16:22 For [only] a few years will pass before I go the way of no return.
18Jb 17:1 My spirit is broken. My days are extinguished. A graveyard awaits me.
18Jb 17:2 Surely mockers surround me and my eyes must gaze at their rebellion.
18Jb 17:3 Make arrangements! Put up security for me. Who [else] will be my sponsor?
18Jb 17:4 You have closed their minds to understanding, therefore You will not honor [them].
18Jb 17:5 If a man informs on his friends for a price, the eyes of his children will fail.
18Jb 17:6 He has made me an object of scorn to the people; I have become a man people spit at.
18Jb 17:7 My eyes have grown dim from grief, and my whole body has become but a shadow.
18Jb 17:8 The upright are appalled at this, and the innocent are roused against the godless.
18Jb 17:9 Yet the righteous person will hold to his way, and the one whose hands are clean will grow stronger.
18Jb 17:10 But come back [and try] again, all of you. I will not find a wise man among you.
18Jb 17:11 My days have slipped by; my plans have been ruined, even the things dear to my heart.
18Jb 17:12 They turned night into day and [made] light [seem] near in the face of darkness.
18Jb 17:13 If I await Sheol as my home, spread out my bed in darkness,
18Jb 17:14 and say to the Pit: You are my father, and to the worm: My mother or my sister,
18Jb 17:15 where then is my hope? Who can see [any] hope for me?
18Jb 17:16 Will it go down to the gates of Sheol, or will we descend together to the dust?
18Jb 18:1 Then Bildad the Shuhite replied:
18Jb 18:2 How long until you stop talking? Show some sense, and then we can talk.
18Jb 18:3 Why are we regarded as cattle, as stupid in your sight?
18Jb 18:4 You who tear yourself in anger-- should the earth be abandoned on your account, or a rock be removed from its place?
18Jb 18:5 Yes, the light of the wicked is extinguished; the flame of his fire does not glow.
18Jb 18:6 The light in his tent grows dark, and the lamp beside him is put out.
18Jb 18:7 His powerful stride is shortened, and his own schemes trip him up.
18Jb 18:8 For his own feet lead him into a net, and he strays into its mesh.
18Jb 18:9 A trap catches [him] by the heel; a noose seizes him.
18Jb 18:10 A rope lies hidden for him on the ground, and a snare [waits] for him along the path.
18Jb 18:11 Terrors frighten him on every side and harass him at every step.
18Jb 18:12 His strength is depleted; disaster lies ready for him to stumble.
18Jb 18:13 Parts of his skin are eaten away; death's firstborn consumes his limbs.
18Jb 18:14 He is ripped from the security of his tent and marched away to the king of terrors.
18Jb 18:15 Nothing he owned remains in his tent. Burning sulfur is scattered over his home.
18Jb 18:16 His roots below dry up, and his branches above wither away.
18Jb 18:17 [All] memory of him perishes from the earth; he has no name abroad.
18Jb 18:18 He is driven from light to darkness and chased from the inhabited world.
18Jb 18:19 He has no children or descendants among his people, no survivor where he used to live.
18Jb 18:20 Those in the west are appalled at his fate, while those in the east tremble in horror.
18Jb 18:21 Indeed, such is the dwelling of the wicked, and this is the place of the one who does not know God.
18Jb 19:1 Then Job answered:
18Jb 19:2 How long will you torment me and crush me with words?
18Jb 19:3 You have humiliated me ten times now, and you mistreat me without shame.
18Jb 19:4 Even if it is true that I have sinned, my mistake concerns only me.
18Jb 19:5 If you really want to appear superior to me and would use my disgrace as evidence against me,
18Jb 19:6 then understand that it is God who has wronged me and caught me in His net.
18Jb 19:7 I cry out: Violence! but get no response; I call for help, but there is no justice.
18Jb 19:8 He has blocked my way so that I cannot pass through; He has veiled my paths with darkness.
18Jb 19:9 He has stripped me of my honor and removed the crown from my head.
18Jb 19:10 He tears me down on every side so that I am ruined. He uproots my hope like a tree.
18Jb 19:11 His anger burns against me, and He regards me as [one of] His enemies.
18Jb 19:12 His troops advance together; they construct a ramp against me and camp around my tent.
18Jb 19:13 He has removed my brothers from me; my acquaintances have abandoned me.
18Jb 19:14 My relatives stop coming by, and my close friends have forgotten me.
18Jb 19:15 My house guests and female servants regard me as a stranger; I am a foreigner in their sight.
18Jb 19:16 I call for my servant, but he does not answer, even if I beg him with my own mouth.
18Jb 19:17 My breath is offensive to my wife, and my own children find me repulsive.
18Jb 19:18 Even young boys scorn me. When I stand up, they mock me.
18Jb 19:19 All of my best friends despise me, and those I love have turned against me.
18Jb 19:20 My skin and my flesh cling to my bones; I have escaped by the skin of my teeth.
18Jb 19:21 Have mercy on me, my friends, have mercy, for God's hand has struck me.
18Jb 19:22 Why do you persecute me as God [does]? Will you never get enough of my flesh?
18Jb 19:23 I wish that my words were written down, that they were recorded on a scroll
18Jb 19:24 or were inscribed in stone forever by an iron stylus and lead!
18Jb 19:25 But I know my living Redeemer, and He will stand on the dust at last.
18Jb 19:26 Even after my skin has been destroyed, yet I will see God in my flesh.
18Jb 19:27 I will see Him myself; my eyes will look at [Him], and not as a stranger. My heart longs within me.
18Jb 19:28 If you say, "How will we pursue him, since the root of the problem lies with him?"
18Jb 19:29 be afraid of the sword, because wrath [brings] punishment by the sword, so that you may know there is a judgment.
18Jb 20:1 Then Zophar the Naamathite replied:
18Jb 20:2 This is why my unsettling thoughts compel me to answer, because I am upset!
18Jb 20:3 I have heard a rebuke that insults me, and my understanding makes me reply.
18Jb 20:4 Don't you know that ever since antiquity, from [the time] man was placed on earth,
18Jb 20:5 the joy of the wicked has been brief and the happiness of the godless has lasted only a moment?
18Jb 20:6 Though his arrogance reaches heaven, and his head touches the clouds,
18Jb 20:7 he will vanish forever like his own dung. Those who know him will ask, "Where is he?"
18Jb 20:8 He will fly away like a dream and never be found; he will be chased away like a vision in the night.
18Jb 20:9 The eye that saw him will see [him] no more, and his household will no longer see him.
18Jb 20:10 His children will beg from the poor, for his own hands must give back his wealth.
18Jb 20:11 His bones may be full of youthful vigor, but it will lie down with him in the grave.
18Jb 20:12 Though evil tastes sweet in his mouth and he conceals it under his tongue,
18Jb 20:13 though he cherishes it and will not let it go but keeps it in his mouth,
18Jb 20:14 yet the food in his stomach turns into cobras' venom inside him.
18Jb 20:15 He swallows wealth but must vomit it up; God will force it from his stomach.
18Jb 20:16 He will suck the poison of cobras; a viper's fangs will kill him.
18Jb 20:17 He will not enjoy the streams, the rivers flowing with honey and cream.
18Jb 20:18 He must return the fruit of his labor without consuming [it]; he doesn't enjoy the profits from his trading.
18Jb 20:19 For he oppressed and abandoned the poor; he seized a house he did not build.
18Jb 20:20 Because his appetite is never satisfied, he does not escape his desires.
18Jb 20:21 Nothing is left for him to consume; therefore, his prosperity will not last.
18Jb 20:22 At the height of his success distress will come to him; the full weight of misery will crush him.
18Jb 20:23 When he fills his stomach, God will send His burning anger against him, raining [it] down on him while he is eating.
18Jb 20:24 If he flees from an iron weapon, [an arrow from] a bronze bow will pierce him.
18Jb 20:25 He pulls it out of his back, the flashing tip out of his liver. Terrors come over him.
18Jb 20:26 Total darkness is reserved for his treasures. A fire unfanned [by human hands] will consume him; it will feed on what is left in his tent.
18Jb 20:27 The heavens will expose his iniquity, and the earth will rise up against him.
18Jb 20:28 The possessions in his house will be removed, flowing away on the day of God's anger.
18Jb 20:29 This is the wicked man's lot from God, the inheritance God ordained for him.
18Jb 21:1 Then Job answered:
18Jb 21:2 Pay close attention to my words; let this be the consolation you offer.
18Jb 21:3 Bear with me while I speak; then after I have spoken, you may continue mocking.
18Jb 21:4 As for me, is my complaint against a man? Then why shouldn't I be impatient?
18Jb 21:5 Look at me and shudder; put [your] hand over [your] mouth.
18Jb 21:6 When I think about [it], I am terrified and my body trembles in horror.
18Jb 21:7 Why do the wicked continue to live, growing old and becoming powerful?
18Jb 21:8 Their children are established while they are still alive, and their descendants, before their eyes.
18Jb 21:9 Their homes are secure and free of fear; no rod from God [strikes] them.
18Jb 21:10 Their bulls breed without fail; their cows calve and do not miscarry.
18Jb 21:11 They let their little ones run around like lambs; their children skip about,
18Jb 21:12 singing to the tambourine and lyre and rejoicing at the sound of the flute.
18Jb 21:13 They spend their days in prosperity and go down to Sheol in peace.
18Jb 21:14 Yet they say to God: "Leave us alone! We don't want to know Your ways.
18Jb 21:15 Who is the Almighty, that we should serve Him, and what will we gain by pleading with Him?"
18Jb 21:16 But their prosperity is not of their own doing. The counsel of the wicked is far from me!
18Jb 21:17 How often is the lamp of the wicked put out? Does disaster come on them? Does He apportion destruction in His anger?
18Jb 21:18 Are they like straw before the wind, like chaff a storm sweeps away?
18Jb 21:19 God reserves a person's punishment for his children. Let God repay the person himself, so that he may know [it].
18Jb 21:20 Let his own eyes see his demise; let him drink from the Almighty's wrath!
18Jb 21:21 For what does he care about his family once he is dead, when the number of his months has run out?
18Jb 21:22 Can anyone teach God knowledge, since He judges the exalted ones?
18Jb 21:23 One person dies in excellent health, completely secure and at ease.
18Jb 21:24 His body is well-fed, and his bones are full of marrow.
18Jb 21:25 Yet another person dies with a bitter soul, having never tasted prosperity.
18Jb 21:26 But they both lie in the dust, and worms cover them.
18Jb 21:27 Look, I know your thoughts, the schemes you would wrong me with.
18Jb 21:28 For you say, "Where now is the nobleman's house?" and "Where are the tents the wicked lived in?"
18Jb 21:29 Have you never consulted those who travel the roads? Don't you accept their reports?
18Jb 21:30 Indeed, the evil man is spared from the day of disaster, rescued from the day of wrath.
18Jb 21:31 Who would denounce his behavior to his face? Who would repay him for what he has done?
18Jb 21:32 He is carried to the grave, and someone keeps watch over [his] tomb.
18Jb 21:33 The dirt on his grave is sweet to him. Everyone follows behind him, and those who go before him are without number.
18Jb 21:34 So how can you offer me such futile comfort? Your answers are deceptive.
18Jb 22:1 Then Eliphaz the Temanite replied:
18Jb 22:2 Can a man be of [any] use to God? Can even a wise man be of use to Him?
18Jb 22:3 Does it delight the Almighty if you are righteous? Does He profit if you perfect your behavior?
18Jb 22:4 Does He correct you and take you to court because of your piety?
18Jb 22:5 Isn't your wickedness abundant and aren't your iniquities endless?
18Jb 22:6 For you took collateral from your brothers without cause, stripping off their clothes and leaving them naked.
18Jb 22:7 You gave no water to the thirsty and withheld food from the famished,
18Jb 22:8 while the land belonged to a powerful man and an influential man lived on it.
18Jb 22:9 You sent widows away empty-handed, and the strength of the fatherless was crushed.
18Jb 22:10 Therefore snares surround you, and sudden dread terrifies you,
18Jb 22:11 or darkness, so you cannot see, and a flood of water covers you.
18Jb 22:12 Isn't God as high as the heavens? And look at the highest stars-- how lofty they are!
18Jb 22:13 Yet you say: "What does God know? Can He judge through thick darkness?
18Jb 22:14 Clouds veil Him so that He cannot see, as He walks on the circle of the sky."
18Jb 22:15 Will you continue on the ancient path that wicked men have walked?
18Jb 22:16 They were snatched away before their time, and their foundations were washed away by a river.
18Jb 22:17 They were the ones who said to God, "Leave us alone!" and "What can the Almighty do to us?"
18Jb 22:18 But it was He who filled their houses with good things. The counsel of the wicked is far from me!
18Jb 22:19 The righteous see [this] and rejoice; the innocent mock them, [saying],
18Jb 22:20 "Surely our opponents are destroyed, and fire has consumed what they left behind."
18Jb 22:21 Come to terms with God and be at peace; in this way good will come to you.
18Jb 22:22 Receive instruction from His mouth, and place His sayings in your heart.
18Jb 22:23 If you return to the Almighty, you will be renewed. If you banish injustice from your tent
18Jb 22:24 and consign your gold to the dust, [the gold of] Ophir to the stones in the wadis,
18Jb 22:25 the Almighty will be your gold and your finest silver.
18Jb 22:26 Then you will delight in the Almighty and lift up your face to God.
18Jb 22:27 You will pray to Him, and He will hear you, and you will fulfill your vows.
18Jb 22:28 When you make a decision, it will be carried out, and light will shine on your ways.
18Jb 22:29 When others are humiliated and you say, "Lift [them] up," God will save the humble.
18Jb 22:30 He will [even] rescue the guilty one, who will be rescued by the purity of your hands.
18Jb 23:1 Then Job answered:
18Jb 23:2 Today also my complaint is bitter. His hand is heavy despite my groaning.
18Jb 23:3 If only I knew how to find Him, so that I could go to His throne.
18Jb 23:4 I would plead my case before Him and fill my mouth with arguments.
18Jb 23:5 I would learn how He would answer me; and understand what He would say to me.
18Jb 23:6 Would He prosecute me forcefully? No, He will certainly pay attention to me.
18Jb 23:7 There an upright man could reason with Him, and I would escape from my Judge forever.
18Jb 23:8 If I go east, He is not there, and if I go west, I cannot perceive Him.
18Jb 23:9 When He is at work to the north, I cannot see Him; when He turns south, I cannot find Him.
18Jb 23:10 Yet He knows the way I have taken; when He has tested me, I will emerge as pure gold.
18Jb 23:11 My feet have followed in His tracks; I have kept to His way and not turned aside.
18Jb 23:12 I have not departed from the commands of His lips; I have treasured the words of His mouth more than my daily food.
18Jb 23:13 But He is unchangeable; who can oppose Him? He does what He desires.
18Jb 23:14 He will certainly accomplish what He has decreed for me, and He has many more things like these in mind.
18Jb 23:15 Therefore I am terrified in His presence; when I consider [this], I am afraid of Him.
18Jb 23:16 God has made my heart faint; the Almighty has terrified me.
18Jb 23:17 Yet I am not destroyed by the darkness, by the thick darkness that covers my face.
18Jb 24:1 Why does the Almighty not reserve times for judgment? Why do those who know Him never see His days?
18Jb 24:2 The wicked displace boundary markers. They steal a flock and provide pasture for [it].
18Jb 24:3 They drive away the donkeys [owned] by the fatherless and take the widow's ox as collateral.
18Jb 24:4 They push the needy off the road; the poor of the land are forced into hiding.
18Jb 24:5 Like wild donkeys in the desert, the poor go out to their task of foraging for food; the wilderness provides nourishment for their children.
18Jb 24:6 They gather their fodder in the field and glean the vineyards of the wicked.
18Jb 24:7 Without clothing, they spend the night naked, having no covering against the cold.
18Jb 24:8 Drenched by mountain rains, they huddle against the rocks, shelterless.
18Jb 24:9 The fatherless infant is snatched from the breast; the nursing child of the poor is seized as collateral.
18Jb 24:10 Without clothing, they wander about naked. They carry sheaves but go hungry.
18Jb 24:11 They crush olives in their presses; they tread the winepresses, but go thirsty.
18Jb 24:12 From the city, men groan; the mortally wounded cry for help, yet God pays no attention to this crime.
18Jb 24:13 The wicked are those who rebel against the light. They do not recognize its ways or stay on its paths.
18Jb 24:14 The murderer rises at dawn to kill the poor and needy, and by night he becomes a thief.
18Jb 24:15 The adulterer's eye watches for twilight, thinking: No eye will see me, he covers [his] face.
18Jb 24:16 In the dark they break into houses; by day they lock themselves in, never experiencing the light.
18Jb 24:17 For the morning is like death's shadow to them. Surely they are familiar with the terrors of death's shadow!
18Jb 24:18 They float on the surface of the water. Their section of the land is cursed, so that they never go to [their] vineyards.
18Jb 24:19 As dry ground and heat snatch away the melted snow, so Sheol [steals] those who have sinned.
18Jb 24:20 The womb forgets them; worms feed on them; they are remembered no more. So injustice is broken like a tree.
18Jb 24:21 They prey on the barren, childless woman and do not deal kindly with the widow.
18Jb 24:22 Yet God drags away the mighty by His power; when He rises up, they have no assurance of life.
18Jb 24:23 He gives them a sense of security, so they can rely [on it], but His eyes [watch] over their ways.
18Jb 24:24 They are exalted for a moment, then they are gone; they are brought low and shrivel up like everything else. They wither like heads of grain.
18Jb 24:25 If this is not true, then who can prove me a liar and show that my speech is worthless?
18Jb 25:1 Then Bildad the Shuhite replied:
18Jb 25:2 Dominion and dread belong to Him, the One who establishes harmony in the heavens.
18Jb 25:3 Can His troops be numbered? Does His light not shine on everyone?
18Jb 25:4 How can a person be justified before God? How can one born of woman be pure?
18Jb 25:5 If even the moon does not shine and the stars are not pure in His sight,
18Jb 25:6 how much less man, who is a maggot, and the son of man, who is a worm!
18Jb 26:1 Then Job answered:
18Jb 26:2 How you have helped the powerless and delivered the arm that is weak!
18Jb 26:3 How you have counseled the unwise and thoroughly explained [the path to] success!
18Jb 26:4 Who did you speak these words to? Whose breath came out of your [mouth]?
18Jb 26:5 The departed spirits tremble beneath the waters and [all] that inhabit them.
18Jb 26:6 Sheol is naked before God, and Abaddon has no covering.
18Jb 26:7 He stretches the northern [skies] over empty space; He hangs the earth on nothing.
18Jb 26:8 He enfolds the waters in His clouds, yet the clouds do not burst beneath their weight.
18Jb 26:9 He obscures the view of [His] throne, spreading His cloud over it.
18Jb 26:10 He laid out the horizon on the surface of the waters at the boundary between light and darkness.
18Jb 26:11 The pillars [that hold up] the sky tremble, astounded at His rebuke.
18Jb 26:12 By His power He stirred the sea, and by His understanding He crushed Rahab.
18Jb 26:13 By His breath the heavens gained their beauty; His hand pierced the fleeing serpent.
18Jb 26:14 These are but the fringes of His ways; how faint is the word we hear of Him! Who can understand His mighty thunder?
18Jb 27:1 Job continued his discourse, saying:
18Jb 27:2 As God lives, who has deprived me of justice, and the Almighty who has made me bitter,
18Jb 27:3 as long as my breath is still in me and the breath from God remains in my nostrils,
18Jb 27:4 my lips will not speak unjustly, and my tongue will not utter deceit.
18Jb 27:5 I will never affirm that you are right. I will maintain my integrity until I die.
18Jb 27:6 I will cling to my righteousness and never let it go. My conscience will not accuse [me] as long as I live!
18Jb 27:7 May my enemy be like the wicked and my opponent like the unjust.
18Jb 27:8 For what hope does the godless man have when he is cut off, when God takes away his life?
18Jb 27:9 Will God hear his cry when distress comes on him?
18Jb 27:10 Will he delight in the Almighty? Will he call on God at all times?
18Jb 27:11 I will teach you about God's power. I will not conceal what the Almighty has planned.
18Jb 27:12 All of you have seen [this] for yourselves, why do you keep up this empty talk?
18Jb 27:13 This is a wicked man's lot from God, the inheritance the ruthless receive from the Almighty.
18Jb 27:14 Even if his children increase, they are destined for the sword; his descendants will never have enough food.
18Jb 27:15 Those who survive him will be buried by the plague, yet their widows will not weep [for them].
18Jb 27:16 Though he piles up silver like dust and heaps up a wardrobe like clay--
18Jb 27:17 he may heap [it] up, but the righteous will wear [it], and the innocent will divide up his silver.
18Jb 27:18 The house he built is like a moth's [cocoon] or a booth set up by a watchman.
18Jb 27:19 He lies down wealthy, but will do so no more; when he opens his eyes, it is gone.
18Jb 27:20 Terrors overtake him like a flood; a storm wind sweeps him away at night.
18Jb 27:21 An east wind picks him up, and he is gone; it carries him away from his place.
18Jb 27:22 It blasts at him without mercy, while he flees desperately from its grasp.
18Jb 27:23 It claps its hands at him and scorns him from its place.
18Jb 28:1 Surely there is a mine for silver and a place where gold is refined.
18Jb 28:2 Iron is taken from the ground, and copper is smelted from ore.
18Jb 28:3 A miner puts an end to the darkness; he probes the deepest recesses for ore in the gloomy darkness.
18Jb 28:4 He cuts a shaft far from human habitation, [in places] unknown to those who walk above ground. Suspended far away from people, the miners swing back and forth.
18Jb 28:5 Food may come from the earth, but below the surface the earth is transformed as by fire.
18Jb 28:6 Its rocks are a source of sapphire, containing flecks of gold.
18Jb 28:7 No bird of prey knows that path; no falcon's eye has seen it.
18Jb 28:8 Proud beasts have never walked on it; no lion has ever prowled over it.
18Jb 28:9 The miner strikes the flint and transforms the mountains at [their] foundations.
18Jb 28:10 He cuts out channels in the rocks, and his eyes spot every treasure.
18Jb 28:11 He dams up the streams from flowing so that he may bring to light what is hidden.
18Jb 28:12 But where can wisdom be found, and where is understanding located?
18Jb 28:13 No man can know its value, since it cannot be found in the land of the living.
18Jb 28:14 The ocean depths say, "It's not in me," while the sea declares, "I don't have it."
18Jb 28:15 Gold cannot be exchanged for it, and silver cannot be weighed out for its price.
18Jb 28:16 Wisdom cannot be valued in the gold of Ophir, in precious onyx or sapphire.
18Jb 28:17 Gold and glass do not compare with it, and articles of fine gold cannot be exchanged for it.
18Jb 28:18 Coral and quartz are not worth mentioning. The price of wisdom is beyond pearls.
18Jb 28:19 Topaz from Cush cannot compare with it, and it cannot be valued in pure gold.
18Jb 28:20 Where then does wisdom come from, and where is understanding located?
18Jb 28:21 It is hidden from the eyes of every living thing and concealed from the birds of the sky.
18Jb 28:22 Abaddon and Death say, "We have heard news of it with our ears."
18Jb 28:23 But God understands the way to wisdom, and He knows its location.
18Jb 28:24 For He looks to the ends of the earth and sees everything under the heavens.
18Jb 28:25 When God fixed the weight of the wind and limited the water by measure,
18Jb 28:26 when He established a limit for the rain and a path for the lightning,
18Jb 28:27 He considered wisdom and evaluated it; He established it and examined it.
18Jb 28:28 He said to mankind, "Look! The fear of the Lord-- that is wisdom, and to turn from evil is understanding."
18Jb 29:1 Job continued his discourse, saying:
18Jb 29:2 If only I could be as in months gone by, in the days when God watched over me,
18Jb 29:3 when His lamp shone above my head, and I walked through darkness by His light!
18Jb 29:4 [I would be] as I was in the days of my youth when God's friendship rested on my tent,
18Jb 29:5 when the Almighty was still with me and my children were around me,
18Jb 29:6 when my feet were bathed in cream and the rock poured out streams of oil for me!
18Jb 29:7 When I went out to the city gate and took my seat in the town square,
18Jb 29:8 the young men saw me and withdrew, while older men stood to their feet.
18Jb 29:9 City officials stopped talking and covered their mouths with [their] hands.
18Jb 29:10 The noblemen's voices were hushed, and their tongues stuck to the roof of their mouths.
18Jb 29:11 When they heard me, they blessed me, and when they saw me, they spoke well of me.
18Jb 29:12 For I rescued the poor man who cried out for help, and the fatherless child who had no one to support him.
18Jb 29:13 The dying man blessed me, and I made the widow's heart rejoice.
18Jb 29:14 I clothed myself in righteousness, and it enveloped me; my just decisions were like a robe and a turban.
18Jb 29:15 I was eyes to the blind and feet to the lame.
18Jb 29:16 I was a father to the needy, and I examined the case of the stranger.
18Jb 29:17 I shattered the fangs of the unjust and snatched the prey from his teeth.
18Jb 29:18 So I thought: I will die in my own nest and multiply [my] days as the sand.
18Jb 29:19 My roots will have access to water, and the dew will rest on my branches all night.
18Jb 29:20 My strength will be refreshed within me, and my bow will be renewed in my hand.
18Jb 29:21 Men listened to me with expectation, waiting silently for my advice.
18Jb 29:22 After a word from me they did not speak again; my speech settled on them [like dew].
18Jb 29:23 They waited for me as for the rain and opened their mouths as for spring showers.
18Jb 29:24 If I smiled at them, they couldn't believe [it]; they were thrilled at the light of my countenance.
18Jb 29:25 I directed their course and presided as chief. I lived as a king among his troops, like one who comforts those who mourn.
18Jb 30:1 But now they mock me, men younger than I am, whose fathers I would have refused to put with my sheep dogs.
18Jb 30:2 What use to me was the strength of their hands? Their vigor had left them.
18Jb 30:3 Emaciated from poverty and hunger, they gnawed the dry land, the desolate wasteland by night.
18Jb 30:4 They plucked mallow among the shrubs, and the roots of the broom tree were their food.
18Jb 30:5 They were expelled from human society; people shouted at them as [if they were] thieves.
18Jb 30:6 They are living on the slopes of the wadis, among the rocks and in holes in the ground.
18Jb 30:7 They bray among the shrubs; they huddle beneath the thistles.
18Jb 30:8 Foolish men, without even a name! They were forced to leave the land.
18Jb 30:9 Now I am mocked by their songs; I have become an object of scorn to them.
18Jb 30:10 They despise me and keep their distance from me; they do not hesitate to spit in my face.
18Jb 30:11 Because God has loosened my bowstring and oppressed me, they have cast off restraint in my presence.
18Jb 30:12 The rabble rise up at my right; they trap my feet and construct their siege ramp against me.
18Jb 30:13 They tear up my path; they contribute to my destruction, without anyone to help them.
18Jb 30:14 They advance as through a gaping breach; they keep rolling in through the ruins.
18Jb 30:15 Terrors are turned loose against me; they chase my dignity away like the wind, and my prosperity has passed by like a cloud.
18Jb 30:16 Now my life is poured out before my [eyes], and days of suffering have seized me.
18Jb 30:17 Night pierces my bones, and my gnawing pains never abate.
18Jb 30:18 My clothing is distorted with great force; He chokes me by the neck of my garment.
18Jb 30:19 He throws me into the mud, and I have become like dust and ashes.
18Jb 30:20 I cry out to You for help, but You do not answer me; when I stand up, You [merely] look at me.
18Jb 30:21 You have turned against me with cruelty; You harass me with Your strong hand.
18Jb 30:22 You lift me up on the wind and make me ride [it]; You scatter me in the storm.
18Jb 30:23 Yes, I know that You will lead me to death-- the place appointed for all who live.
18Jb 30:24 Yet no one would stretch out [his] hand against a ruined man when he cries out to him for help because of his distress.
18Jb 30:25 Have I not wept for those who have fallen on hard times? Has my soul not grieved for the needy?
18Jb 30:26 But when I hoped for good, evil came; when I looked for light, darkness came.
18Jb 30:27 I am churning within and cannot rest; days of suffering confront me.
18Jb 30:28 I walk about blackened, but not by the sun. I stood in the assembly and cried out for help.
18Jb 30:29 I have become a brother to jackals and a companion of ostriches.
18Jb 30:30 My skin blackens and flakes off, and my bones burn with fever.
18Jb 30:31 My lyre is [used] for mourning and my flute for the sound of weeping.
18Jb 31:1 I have made a covenant with my eyes. How then could I look at a young woman?
18Jb 31:2 For what portion [would I have] from God above, or [what] inheritance from the Almighty on high?
18Jb 31:3 Doesn't disaster come to the wicked and misfortune to evildoers?
18Jb 31:4 Does He not see my ways and number all my steps?
18Jb 31:5 If I have walked in falsehood or my foot has rushed to deceit,
18Jb 31:6 let God weigh me with an accurate balance, and He will recognize my integrity.
18Jb 31:7 If my step has turned from the way, my heart has followed my eyes, or impurity has stained my hands,
18Jb 31:8 let someone else eat what I have sown, and let my crops be uprooted.
18Jb 31:9 If my heart has been seduced by [my neighbor's] wife or I have lurked at his door,
18Jb 31:10 let my own wife grind [grain] for another man, and let other men sleep with her.
18Jb 31:11 For that would be a disgrace; it would be a crime deserving punishment.
18Jb 31:12 For it is a fire that consumes down to Abaddon; it would destroy my entire harvest.
18Jb 31:13 If I have dismissed the case of my male or female servants when they made a complaint against me,
18Jb 31:14 what could I do when God stands up [to judge]? How should I answer Him when He calls [me] to account?
18Jb 31:15 Did not the One who made me in the womb also make them? Did not the same God form us both in the womb?
18Jb 31:16 If I have refused the wishes of the poor or let the widow's eyes go blind,
18Jb 31:17 if I have eaten my few crumbs alone without letting the fatherless eat any of it--
18Jb 31:18 for from my youth, I raised him as [his] father, and since the day I was born I guided the widow--
18Jb 31:19 if I have seen anyone dying for lack of clothing or a needy person without a cloak,
18Jb 31:20 if he did not bless me while warming himself with the fleece from my sheep,
18Jb 31:21 if I ever cast my vote against a fatherless child when I saw that I had support in the [city] gate,
18Jb 31:22 then let my shoulder blade fall from my back, and my arm be pulled from its socket.
18Jb 31:23 For disaster from God terrifies me, and because of His majesty I could not do [these things].
18Jb 31:24 If I placed my confidence in gold or called fine gold my trust,
18Jb 31:25 if I have rejoiced because my wealth is great or because my own hand has acquired [so] much,
18Jb 31:26 if I have gazed at the sun when it was shining or at the moon moving in splendor,
18Jb 31:27 so that my heart was secretly enticed and I threw them a kiss,
18Jb 31:28 this would also be a crime deserving punishment, for I would have denied God above.
18Jb 31:29 Have I rejoiced over my enemy's distress, or become excited when trouble came his way?
18Jb 31:30 I have not allowed my mouth to sin by asking for his life with a curse.
18Jb 31:31 Haven't the members of my household said, "Who is there who has not had enough to eat at Job's table?"
18Jb 31:32 No stranger had to spend the night on the street, for I opened my door to the traveler.
18Jb 31:33 Have I covered my transgressions as others do by hiding my guilt in my heart,
18Jb 31:34 because I greatly feared the crowds, and the contempt of the clans terrified me, so I grew silent and would not go outside?
18Jb 31:35 If only I had someone to hear my [case]! Here is my signature; let the Almighty answer me. Let my Opponent compose [His] indictment.
18Jb 31:36 I would surely carry it on my shoulder and wear it like a crown.
18Jb 31:37 I would give Him an account of all my steps; I would approach Him like a prince.
18Jb 31:38 If my land cries out against me and its furrows join in weeping,
18Jb 31:39 if I have consumed its produce without payment or shown contempt for its tenants,
18Jb 31:40 then let thorns grow instead of wheat and stinkweed instead of barley. The words of Job are concluded.
18Jb 32:1 So these three men quit answering Job, because he was righteous in his own eyes.
18Jb 32:2 Then Elihu son of Barachel the Buzite from the family of Ram became angry. He was angry at Job because he had justified himself rather than God.
18Jb 32:3 He was also angry at Job's three friends because they had failed to refute [him], and yet had condemned him.
18Jb 32:4 Now Elihu had waited to speak to Job because they were [all] older than he.
18Jb 32:5 But when he saw that the three men could not answer Job, he became angry.
18Jb 32:6 So Elihu son of Barachel the Buzite replied: I am young in years, while you are old; therefore I was timid and afraid to tell you what I know.
18Jb 32:7 I thought that age should speak and maturity should teach wisdom.
18Jb 32:8 But it is a spirit in man and the breath of the Almighty that give him understanding.
18Jb 32:9 It is not [only] the old who are wise or the elderly who understand how to judge.
18Jb 32:10 Therefore I say, "Listen to me. I too will declare what I know."
18Jb 32:11 Look, I waited for your conclusions; I listened to your insights as you sought for words.
18Jb 32:12 I paid close attention to you. Yet no one proved Job wrong; not one of you refuted his arguments.
18Jb 32:13 So do not claim, "We have found wisdom; let God deal with him, not man."
18Jb 32:14 But Job has not directed his argument to me, and I will not respond to him with your arguments.
18Jb 32:15 Job's friends are dismayed and can no longer answer; words have left them.
18Jb 32:16 Should I continue to wait now that they are silent, now that they stand [there] and no longer answer?
18Jb 32:17 I too will answer; yes, I will tell what I know.
18Jb 32:18 For I am full of words, and my spirit compels me [to speak].
18Jb 32:19 My heart is like unvented wine; it is about to burst like new wineskins.
18Jb 32:20 I must speak so that I can find relief; I must open my lips and respond.
18Jb 32:21 I will be partial to no one, and I will not give anyone an [undeserved] title.
18Jb 32:22 For I do not know how to give [such] titles; otherwise, my Maker would remove me in an instant.
18Jb 33:1 But now, Job, pay attention to my speech, and listen to all my words.
18Jb 33:2 I am going to open my mouth; my tongue will form words on my palate.
18Jb 33:3 My words [come from] my upright heart, and my lips speak what they know with sincerity.
18Jb 33:4 The Spirit of God has made me, and the breath of the Almighty gives me life.
18Jb 33:5 Refute me if you can. Prepare your case against me; take your stand.
18Jb 33:6 I am just like you before God; I was also pinched off from [a piece of] clay.
18Jb 33:7 Fear of me should not terrify you; the pressure I exert against you will be light.
18Jb 33:8 Surely you have spoken in my hearing, and I have heard these very words:
18Jb 33:9 "I am pure, without transgression; I am clean and have no guilt.
18Jb 33:10 But He finds reasons to oppose me; He regards me as his enemy.
18Jb 33:11 He puts my feet in the stocks; He stands watch over all my paths."
18Jb 33:12 But I tell you that you are wrong in this [matter], since God is greater than man.
18Jb 33:13 Why do you take Him to court for not answering anything a person asks?
18Jb 33:14 For God speaks time and again, but a person may not notice it.
18Jb 33:15 In a dream, a vision in the night, when deep sleep falls on people as they slumber on [their] beds,
18Jb 33:16 He uncovers their ears at that time and terrifies them with warnings,
18Jb 33:17 in order to turn a person [from his] actions and suppress his pride.
18Jb 33:18 God spares his soul from the Pit, his life from crossing the river [of death].
18Jb 33:19 A person may be disciplined on his bed with pain and constant distress in his bones,
18Jb 33:20 so that he detests bread, and his soul [despises his] favorite food.
18Jb 33:21 His flesh wastes away to nothing, and his unseen bones stick out.
18Jb 33:22 He draws near the Pit, and his life to the executioners.
18Jb 33:23 If there is an angel on his side, one mediator out of a thousand, to tell a person what is right for him
18Jb 33:24 and to be gracious to him and say, "Spare him from going down to the Pit; I have found a ransom,"
18Jb 33:25 then his flesh will be healthier than in his youth, and he will return to the days of his youthful vigor.
18Jb 33:26 He will pray to God, and God will delight in him. That man will behold His face with a shout of joy, and God will restore his righteousness to him.
18Jb 33:27 He will look at men and say, "I have sinned and perverted what was right; yet I did not get what I deserved.
18Jb 33:28 He redeemed my soul from going down to the Pit, and I will continue to see the light."
18Jb 33:29 God certainly does all these things two or three times to a man
18Jb 33:30 in order to turn him back from the Pit, so he may shine with the light of life.
18Jb 33:31 Pay attention, Job, and listen to me. Be quiet, and I will speak.
18Jb 33:32 But if you have something to say, answer me; speak, for I would like to justify you.
18Jb 33:33 If not, then listen to me; be quiet, and I will teach you wisdom.
18Jb 34:1 Then Elihu continued, saying:
18Jb 34:2 Hear my words, you wise men, and listen to me, you knowledgeable ones.
18Jb 34:3 Doesn't the ear tests words as the palate tastes food?
18Jb 34:4 Let us judge for ourselves what is right; let us decide together what is good.
18Jb 34:5 For Job has declared, "I am righteous, yet God has deprived me of justice.
18Jb 34:6 Would I lie about my case? My wound is incurable, though I am without transgression."
18Jb 34:7 What man is like Job? He drinks derision like water.
18Jb 34:8 He keeps company with evildoers and walks with wicked men.
18Jb 34:9 For he has said, "A man gains nothing when he becomes God's friend."
18Jb 34:10 Therefore listen to me, you men of understanding. It is impossible for God [to do] wrong, and [for] the Almighty [to act] unjustly.
18Jb 34:11 For He repays a person [according to] his deeds, and He bring his ways on him.
18Jb 34:12 Indeed, it is true that God does not act wickedly and the Almighty does not pervert justice.
18Jb 34:13 Who gave Him authority over the earth? Who put Him in charge of the entire world?
18Jb 34:14 If He put His mind to it and withdrew the spirit and breath He [gave],
18Jb 34:15 every living thing would perish together and mankind would return to the dust.
18Jb 34:16 If you [have] understanding, hear this; listen to what I have to say.
18Jb 34:17 Could one who hates justice govern [the world]? Will you condemn the mighty Righteous One,
18Jb 34:18 who says to a king, "Worthless man!" and to nobles, "Wicked men!"?
18Jb 34:19 God is not partial to princes and does not favor the rich over the poor, for they are all the work of His hands.
18Jb 34:20 They die suddenly in the middle of the night; people shudder, then pass away. Even the mighty are removed without effort.
18Jb 34:21 For His eyes [watch] over a man's ways, and He observes all his steps.
18Jb 34:22 There is no darkness, no deep darkness, where evildoers can hide themselves.
18Jb 34:23 God does not [need to] examine a person further, that one should approach Him in court.
18Jb 34:24 He shatters the mighty without an investigation and sets others in their place.
18Jb 34:25 Therefore, He recognizes their deeds and overthrows [them] by night, and they are crushed.
18Jb 34:26 In full view of the public, He strikes them for their wickedness,
18Jb 34:27 because they turned aside from following Him and did not understand any of His ways
18Jb 34:28 but caused the poor to cry out to Him, and He heard the outcry of the afflicted.
18Jb 34:29 But when God is silent, who can declare [Him] guilty? When He hides [His] face, who can see Him? Yet He [watches] over both individuals and nations,
18Jb 34:30 so that godless men should not rule or ensnare the people.
18Jb 34:31 Suppose someone says to God, "I have endured [my punishment]; I will no [longer] act wickedly.
18Jb 34:32 Teach me what I cannot see; if I have done wrong, I won't do it again."
18Jb 34:33 Should God repay [you] on your terms when you have rejected [His]? You must choose, not I! So declare what you know.
18Jb 34:34 Reasonable men will say to me, along with the wise men who hear me,
18Jb 34:35 "Job speaks without knowledge; his words are without insight."
18Jb 34:36 If only Job were tested to the limit, because [his] answers are [like] those of wicked men.
18Jb 34:37 For he adds rebellion to his sin; he [scornfully] claps in our presence, while multiplying his words against God.
18Jb 35:1 Then Elihu continued, saying:
18Jb 35:2 Do you think it is just when you say, "I am righteous before God"?
18Jb 35:3 For you ask, "What does it profit You, and what benefit comes to me, if I do not sin?"
18Jb 35:4 I will answer you and your friends with you.
18Jb 35:5 Look at the heavens and see; gaze at the clouds high above you.
18Jb 35:6 If you sin, how does it affect God? If you multiply your transgressions, what does it do to Him?
18Jb 35:7 If you are righteous, what do you give Him, or what does He receive from your hand?
18Jb 35:8 Your wickedness [affects] a person like yourself, and your righteousness [another] human being.
18Jb 35:9 People cry out because of severe oppression; they shout for help from the arm of the mighty.
18Jb 35:10 But no one asks, "Where is God my Maker, who provides [us] with songs in the night,
18Jb 35:11 who gives us more understanding than the animals of the earth and makes us wiser than the birds of the sky?"
18Jb 35:12 There they cry out, but He does not answer, because of the pride of evil men.
18Jb 35:13 Indeed, God does not listen to empty [cries], and the Almighty does not take note of it--
18Jb 35:14 how much less when you complain that you do not see Him, [that your] case is before Him and you are waiting for Him.
18Jb 35:15 But now, because God's anger does not punish and He does not pay attention to transgression,
18Jb 35:16 Job opens his mouth in vain and multiplies words without knowledge.
18Jb 36:1 Then Elihu continued, saying:
18Jb 36:2 Be patient with me a little longer, and I will inform you, for there is still more to be said on God's behalf.
18Jb 36:3 I will get my knowledge from afar and ascribe righteousness to my Maker.
18Jb 36:4 For my arguments are without flaw; one who has perfect knowledge is with you.
18Jb 36:5 Yes, God is mighty, but He despises [no one]; He understands all things.
18Jb 36:6 He does not keep the wicked alive, but He gives justice to the afflicted.
18Jb 36:7 He does not remove His gaze from the righteous, but He seats them forever with enthroned kings, and they are exalted.
18Jb 36:8 If people are bound with chains and trapped by the cords of affliction,
18Jb 36:9 God tells them what they have done and how arrogantly they have transgressed.
18Jb 36:10 He opens their ears to correction and insists they repent from iniquity.
18Jb 36:11 If they serve Him obediently, they will end their days in prosperity and their years in happiness.
18Jb 36:12 But if they do not obey, they will cross the river [of death] and die without knowledge.
18Jb 36:13 Those who have a godless heart harbor anger; even when God binds them, they do not cry for help.
18Jb 36:14 They die in their youth; their life [ends] among male cult prostitutes.
18Jb 36:15 God rescues the afflicted by afflicting them; He instructs them by means of their torment.
18Jb 36:16 Indeed, He lured you from the jaws of distress to a spacious and unconfined place. Your table was spread with choice food.
18Jb 36:17 Yet [now] you are obsessed with the judgment due the wicked; judgment and justice have seized you.
18Jb 36:18 Be careful that no one lures you with riches; do not let a large ransom lead you astray.
18Jb 36:19 Can your wealth or all [your] physical exertion keep [you] from distress?
18Jb 36:20 Do not long for the night when nations will disappear from their places.
18Jb 36:21 Be careful that you do not turn to iniquity, for that is why you have been tested by affliction.
18Jb 36:22 Look, God shows Himself exalted by His power. Who is a teacher like Him?
18Jb 36:23 Who has appointed His way for Him, and who has declared, "You have done wrong"?
18Jb 36:24 Remember that you should praise His work, which people have sung about.
18Jb 36:25 All mankind has seen it; people have looked at it from a distance.
18Jb 36:26 Look, God is exalted beyond our knowledge; the number of His years cannot be counted.
18Jb 36:27 For He makes waterdrops evaporate; they distill the rain into its mist,
18Jb 36:28 which the clouds pour out and shower abundantly on mankind.
18Jb 36:29 Can anyone understand how the clouds spread out or how the thunder roars from God's pavilion?
18Jb 36:30 Look, He spreads His lightning around Him and covers the depths of the sea.
18Jb 36:31 For He judges the nations with these; He gives food in abundance.
18Jb 36:32 He covers [His] hands with lightning and commands it to hit its mark.
18Jb 36:33 The thunder declares His presence; the cattle also, the approaching [storm].
18Jb 37:1 My heart pounds at this and leaps from my chest.
18Jb 37:2 Just listen to His thunderous voice and the rumbling that comes from His mouth.
18Jb 37:3 He lets it loose beneath the entire sky; His lightning to the ends of the earth.
18Jb 37:4 Then there comes a roaring sound; God thunders with His majestic voice. He does not restrain the lightning when His [rumbling] voice is heard.
18Jb 37:5 God thunders marvelously with His voice; He does great things that we cannot comprehend.
18Jb 37:6 For He says to the snow, "Fall to the earth," and the torrential rains, His mighty torrential rains,
18Jb 37:7 serve as His signature to all mankind, so that all men may know His work.
18Jb 37:8 The wild animals enter [their] lairs and stay in their dens.
18Jb 37:9 The windstorm comes from its chamber, and the cold from the driving north winds.
18Jb 37:10 Ice is formed by the breath of God, and watery expanses are frozen.
18Jb 37:11 He saturates clouds with moisture; He scatters His lightning through them.
18Jb 37:12 They swirl about, turning round and round at His direction, accomplishing everything He commands them over the surface of the inhabited world.
18Jb 37:13 He causes this to happen for punishment, for His land, or for His faithful love.
18Jb 37:14 Listen to this, Job. Stop and consider God's wonders.
18Jb 37:15 Do you know how God directs His clouds or makes their lightning flash?
18Jb 37:16 Do you understand how the clouds float, those wonderful works of Him who has perfect knowledge?
18Jb 37:17 You whose clothes get hot when the south wind brings calm to the land,
18Jb 37:18 can you help God spread out the skies as hard as a cast metal mirror?
18Jb 37:19 Teach us what we should say to Him; we cannot prepare [our case] because of our darkness.
18Jb 37:20 Should He be told that I want to speak? Can a man speak when he is confused?
18Jb 37:21 Now men cannot [even] look at the sun when it is in the skies, after a wind has swept through and cleared them away.
18Jb 37:22 Yet out of the north He comes, [shrouded] in a golden [glow]; awesome majesty surrounds Him.
18Jb 37:23 The Almighty-- we cannot reach Him-- He is exalted in power! In His justice and righteousness, He will not oppress.
18Jb 37:24 Therefore, men fear Him. He does not look favorably on any who are wise in heart.
18Jb 38:1 Then the LORD answered Job from the whirlwind. He said:
18Jb 38:2 Who is this who obscures [My] counsel with ignorant words?
18Jb 38:3 Get ready to answer Me like a man; when I question you, you will inform Me.
18Jb 38:4 Where were you when I established the earth? Tell [Me], if you have understanding.
18Jb 38:5 Who fixed its dimensions? Certainly you know! Who stretched a measuring line across it?
18Jb 38:6 What supports its foundations? Or who laid its cornerstone
18Jb 38:7 while the morning stars sang together and all the sons of God shouted for joy?
18Jb 38:8 Who enclosed the sea behind doors when it burst from the womb,
18Jb 38:9 when I made the clouds its garment and thick darkness its blanket,
18Jb 38:10 when I determined its boundaries and put [its] bars and doors in place,
18Jb 38:11 when I declared: "You may come this far, but no farther; your proud waves stop here"?
18Jb 38:12 Have you ever in your life commanded the morning or assigned the dawn its place,
18Jb 38:13 so it may seize the edges of the earth and shake the wicked out of it?
18Jb 38:14 The earth is changed as clay is by a seal; [its hills] stand out like [the folds of] a garment.
18Jb 38:15 Light is withheld from the wicked, and the arm raised [in violence] is broken.
18Jb 38:16 Have you traveled to the sources of the sea or walked in the depths of the oceans?
18Jb 38:17 Have the gates of death been revealed to you? Have you seen the gates of death's shadow?
18Jb 38:18 Have you comprehended the extent of the earth? Tell [Me], if you know all this.
18Jb 38:19 Where is the road to the home of light? [Do you know] where darkness lives,
18Jb 38:20 so you can lead it back to its border? Are you familiar with the paths to its home?
18Jb 38:21 Don't you know? You were already born; you have lived so long!
18Jb 38:22 Have you entered the [place] where the snow is stored? Or have you seen the storehouses of hail,
18Jb 38:23 which I hold in reserve for times of trouble, for the day of warfare and battle?
18Jb 38:24 What road leads to [the place] where light is dispersed? [Where is the source of] the east wind that spreads across the earth?
18Jb 38:25 Who cuts a channel for the flooding rain or clears the way for lightning,
18Jb 38:26 to bring rain on an uninhabited land, [on] a desert with no human life,
18Jb 38:27 to satisfy the parched wasteland and cause the grass to sprout?
18Jb 38:28 Does the rain have a father? Who fathered the drops of dew?
18Jb 38:29 Whose womb did the ice come from? Who gave birth to the frost of heaven
18Jb 38:30 when water becomes as hard as stone, and the surface of the watery depths is frozen?
18Jb 38:31 Can you fasten the chains of the Pleiades or loosen the belt of Orion?
18Jb 38:32 Can you bring out the constellations in their season and lead the Bear and her cubs?
18Jb 38:33 Do you know the laws of heaven? Can you impose its authority on earth?
18Jb 38:34 Can you command the clouds so that a flood of water covers you?
18Jb 38:35 Can you send out lightning bolts, and they go? Do they report to you: "Here we are"?
18Jb 38:36 Who put wisdom in the heart or gave the mind understanding?
18Jb 38:37 Who has the wisdom to number the clouds? Or who can tilt the water jars of heaven
18Jb 38:38 when the dust hardens like cast metal and the clods [of dirt] stick together?
18Jb 38:39 Can you hunt prey for a lioness or satisfy the appetite of young lions
18Jb 38:40 when they crouch in their dens and lie in wait within their lairs?
18Jb 38:41 Who provides the raven's food when its young cry out to God and wander about for lack of food?
18Jb 39:1 Do you know when mountain goats give birth? Have you watched the deer in labor?
18Jb 39:2 Can you count the months they are pregnant so you can know the time they give birth?
18Jb 39:3 They crouch down to give birth to their young; they deliver their newborn.
18Jb 39:4 Their offspring are healthy and grow up in the open field. They leave and do not return.
18Jb 39:5 Who set the wild donkey free? Who released the swift donkey from its harness?
18Jb 39:6 I made the wilderness its home, and the salty wasteland its dwelling.
18Jb 39:7 It scoffs at the noise of the village and never hears the shouts of a driver.
18Jb 39:8 It roams the mountains for its pastureland, searching for anything green.
18Jb 39:9 Would the wild ox be willing to serve you? Would it spend the night by your feeding trough?
18Jb 39:10 Can you hold the wild ox by its harness to the furrow? Will it plow the valleys behind you?
18Jb 39:11 Can you depend on it because of its strength? Would you leave it to do your hard work?
18Jb 39:12 Can you trust the wild ox to harvest your grain and bring [it] to your threshing floor?
18Jb 39:13 The wings of the ostrich flap joyfully, but are her feathers and plumage like the stork's?
18Jb 39:14 She abandons her eggs on the ground and lets them be warmed in the sand.
18Jb 39:15 She forgets that a foot may crush them or that some wild animal may trample them.
18Jb 39:16 She treats her young harshly, as if [they] were not her own, with no fear that her labor may have been in vain.
18Jb 39:17 For God has deprived her of wisdom; He has not endowed her with understanding.
18Jb 39:18 When she proudly spreads her wings, she laughs at the horse and its rider.
18Jb 39:19 Do you give strength to the horse? Do you adorn his neck with a mane?
18Jb 39:20 Do you make him leap like a locust? His proud snorting [fills one with] terror.
18Jb 39:21 He paws in the valley and rejoices in his strength; He charges into battle.
18Jb 39:22 He laughs at fear, since he is afraid of nothing; he does not run from the sword.
18Jb 39:23 A quiver rattles at his side, along with a flashing spear and a lance.
18Jb 39:24 He charges ahead with trembling rage; he cannot stand still at the trumpet's sound.
18Jb 39:25 When the trumpet blasts, he snorts defiantly. He smells the battle from a distance; he hears the officers' shouts and the battle cry.
18Jb 39:26 Does the hawk take flight by your understanding and spread its wings to the south?
18Jb 39:27 Does the eagle soar at your command and make its nest on high?
18Jb 39:28 It lives on a cliff where it spends the night; its stronghold is on a rocky crag.
18Jb 39:29 From there it searches for prey; its eyes penetrate the distance.
18Jb 39:30 Its brood gulps down blood, and wherever corpses lie, it is there.
18Jb 40:1 The LORD answered Job:
18Jb 40:2 Will the one who contends with the Almighty correct [Him]? Let him who argues with God give an answer.
18Jb 40:3 Then Job answered the Lord:
18Jb 40:4 I am so insignificant. How can I answer You? I place my hand over my mouth.
18Jb 40:5 I have spoken once, and I will not reply; twice, but [now] I can add nothing.
18Jb 40:6 Then the LORD answered Job from the whirlwind:
18Jb 40:7 Get ready to answer Me like a man; When I question you, you will inform Me.
18Jb 40:8 Would you really challenge My justice? Would you declare Me guilty to justify yourself?
18Jb 40:9 Do you have an arm like God's? Can you thunder with a voice like His?
18Jb 40:10 Adorn yourself with majesty and splendor, and clothe yourself with honor and glory.
18Jb 40:11 Unleash your raging anger; look on every proud person and humiliate him.
18Jb 40:12 Look on every proud person and humble him; trample the wicked where they stand.
18Jb 40:13 Hide them together in the dust; imprison them in the grave.
18Jb 40:14 Then I will confess to you that your own right hand can deliver you.
18Jb 40:15 Look at Behemoth, which I made along with you. He eats grass like an ox.
18Jb 40:16 Look at the strength of his loins and the power in the muscles of his belly.
18Jb 40:17 He stiffens his tail like a cedar tree; the tendons of his thighs are woven firmly together.
18Jb 40:18 His bones are bronze tubes; his limbs are like iron rods.
18Jb 40:19 He is the foremost of God's works; [only] his Maker can draw the sword against him.
18Jb 40:20 The hills yield food for him, while all [sorts of] wild animals play there.
18Jb 40:21 He lies under the lotus plants, hiding in the protection of marshy reeds.
18Jb 40:22 Lotus plants cover him with their shade; the willows by the brook surround him.
18Jb 40:23 Though the river rages, Behemoth is unafraid; he remains confident, even if the Jordan surges up to his mouth.
18Jb 40:24 Can anyone capture him while he looks on, or pierce his nose with snares?
18Jb 41:1  Can you pull in Leviathan with a hook or tie his tongue down with a rope?
18Jb 41:2 Can you put a cord through his nose or pierce his jaw with a hook?
18Jb 41:3 Will he beg you for mercy or speak softly to you?
18Jb 41:4 Will he make a covenant with you so that you can take him as a slave forever?
18Jb 41:5 Can you play with him like a bird or put him on a leash for your girls?
18Jb 41:6 Will traders bargain for him or divide him among the merchants?
18Jb 41:7 Can you fill his hide with harpoons or his head with fishing spears?
18Jb 41:8 Lay a hand on him. You will remember the battle and never repeat it!
18Jb 41:9  Any hope of [capturing] him proves false. Does a person not collapse at the very sight of him?
18Jb 41:10 No one is ferocious [enough] to rouse Leviathan; who then can stand against Me?
18Jb 41:11 Who confronted Me, that I should repay him? Everything under heaven belongs to Me.
18Jb 41:12 I cannot be silent about his limbs, his power, and his graceful proportions.
18Jb 41:13 Who can strip off his outer covering? Who can penetrate his double layer of armor?
18Jb 41:14 Who can open his jaws, surrounded by those terrifying teeth?
18Jb 41:15 [His] pride is in [his] rows of scales, closely sealed together.
18Jb 41:16 One scale is so close to another that no air can pass between them.
18Jb 41:17 They are joined to one another, so closely connected they cannot be separated.
18Jb 41:18 His snorting flashes with light, while his eyes are like the rays of dawn.
18Jb 41:19 Flaming torches shoot from his mouth; fiery sparks fly out!
18Jb 41:20 Smoke billows from his nostrils as from a boiling pot or [burning] reeds.
18Jb 41:21 His breath sets coals ablaze, and flames pour out of his mouth.
18Jb 41:22 Strength resides in his neck, and dismay dances before him.
18Jb 41:23 The folds of his flesh are joined together, solid as metal and immovable.
18Jb 41:24 His heart is as hard as a rock, as hard as a lower millstone!
18Jb 41:25 When Leviathan rises, the mighty are terrified; they withdraw because of [his] thrashing.
18Jb 41:26 The sword that reaches him will have no effect, nor will a spear, dart, or arrow.
18Jb 41:27 He regards iron as straw, and bronze as rotten wood.
18Jb 41:28 No arrow can make him flee; slingstones become like stubble to him.
18Jb 41:29 A club is regarded as stubble, and he laughs at the whirring of a javelin.
18Jb 41:30 His undersides are jagged potsherds, spreading the mud like a threshing sledge.
18Jb 41:31 He makes the depths seethe like a caldron; he makes the sea like an ointment jar.
18Jb 41:32 He leaves a shining wake behind him; one would think the deep had white hair!
18Jb 41:33 He has no equal on earth-- a creature devoid of fear!
18Jb 41:34 He surveys everything that is haughty; he is king over all the proud beasts.
18Jb 42:1 Then Job replied to the LORD:
18Jb 42:2 I know that You can do anything and no plan of Yours can be thwarted.
18Jb 42:3 [You asked,] "Who is this who conceals [My] counsel with ignorance?" Surely I spoke about things I did not understand, things too wonderful for me to know.
18Jb 42:4 [You said,] "Listen now, and I will speak. When I question you, you will inform Me."
18Jb 42:5 I had heard rumors about You, but now my eyes have seen You.
18Jb 42:6 Therefore I take back [my words] and repent in dust and ashes.
18Jb 42:7 After the LORD had finished speaking to Job, He said to Eliphaz the Temanite: "I am angry with you and your two friends, for you have not spoken the truth about Me, as My servant Job has.
18Jb 42:8 Now take seven bulls and seven rams, go to My servant Job, and offer a burnt offering for yourselves. Then My servant Job will pray for you. I will surely accept his [prayer] and not deal with you as your folly deserves. For you have not spoken the truth about Me, as My servant Job has."
18Jb 42:9 Then Eliphaz the Temanite, Bildad the Shuhite, and Zophar the Naamathite went and did as the LORD had told them, and the LORD accepted Job's [prayer].
18Jb 42:10 After Job had prayed for his friends, the LORD restored his prosperity and doubled his [previous] possessions.
18Jb 42:11 All his brothers, sisters, and former acquaintances came to his house and dined with him in his house. They offered him sympathy and comfort concerning all the adversity the LORD had brought on him. Each one gave him a qesitah, and a gold earring.
18Jb 42:12 So the LORD blessed the latter part of Job's life more than the earlier. He owned 14,000 sheep, 6,000 camels, 1,000 yoke of oxen, and 1,000 female donkeys.
18Jb 42:13 He also had seven sons and three daughters.
18Jb 42:14 He named his first [daughter] Jemimah, his second Keziah, and his third Keren-happuch.
18Jb 42:15 No women as beautiful as Job's daughters could be found in all the land, and their father granted them an inheritance with their brothers.
18Jb 42:16 Job lived 140 years after this and saw his children and their children to the fourth generation.
18Jb 42:17 Then Job died, old and full of days.
