20Pr 1:1 The proverbs of Solomon son of David, king of Israel:
20Pr 1:2 For gaining wisdom and being instructed; for understanding insightful sayings;
20Pr 1:3 for receiving wise instruction [in] righteousness, justice, and integrity;
20Pr 1:4 for teaching shrewdness to the inexperienced, knowledge and discretion to a young man--
20Pr 1:5 a wise man will listen and increase his learning, and a discerning man will obtain guidance--
20Pr 1:6 for understanding a proverb or a parable, the words of the wise, and their riddles.
20Pr 1:7 The fear of the LORD is the beginning of knowledge; fools despise wisdom and instruction.
20Pr 1:8 Listen, my son, to your father's instruction, and don't reject your mother's teaching,
20Pr 1:9 for they will be a garland of grace on your head and a [gold] chain around your neck.
20Pr 1:10 My son, if sinners entice you, don't be persuaded.
20Pr 1:11 If they say-- "Come with us! Let's set an ambush and kill someone. Let's attack some innocent person just for fun!
20Pr 1:12 Let's swallow them alive, like Sheol, still healthy as they go down to the Pit.
20Pr 1:13 We'll find all kinds of valuable property and fill our houses with plunder.
20Pr 1:14 Throw in your lot with us, and we'll all share our money"--
20Pr 1:15 my son, don't travel that road with them or set foot on their path,
20Pr 1:16 because their feet run toward trouble and they hurry to commit murder.
20Pr 1:17 It is foolish to spread a net where any bird can see it,
20Pr 1:18 but they set an ambush to kill themselves; they attack their own lives.
20Pr 1:19 Such are the paths of all who pursue gain dishonestly; it takes the lives of those who profit from it.
20Pr 1:20 Wisdom calls out in the street; she raises her voice in the public squares.
20Pr 1:21 She cries out above the commotion; she speaks at the entrance of the city gates:
20Pr 1:22 "How long, foolish ones, will you love ignorance? [How long] will [you] mockers enjoy mocking and [you] fools hate knowledge?
20Pr 1:23 If you turn to my discipline, then I will pour out my spirit on you and teach you my words.
20Pr 1:24 Since I called out and you refused, extended my hand and no one paid attention,
20Pr 1:25 since you neglected all my counsel and did not accept my correction,
20Pr 1:26 I, in turn, will laugh at your calamity. I will mock when terror strikes you,
20Pr 1:27 when terror strikes you like a storm and your calamity comes like a whirlwind, when trouble and stress overcome you.
20Pr 1:28 Then they will call me, but I won't answer; they will search for me, but won't find me.
20Pr 1:29 Because they hated knowledge, didn't choose to fear the LORD,
20Pr 1:30 were not interested in my counsel, and rejected all my correction,
20Pr 1:31 they will eat the fruit of their way and be glutted with their own schemes.
20Pr 1:32 For the waywardness of the inexperienced will kill them, and the complacency of fools will destroy them.
20Pr 1:33 But whoever listens to me will live securely and be free from the fear of danger."
20Pr 2:1 My son, if you accept my words and store up my commands within you,
20Pr 2:2 listening closely to wisdom and directing your heart to understanding;
20Pr 2:3 furthermore, if you call out to insight and lift your voice to understanding,
20Pr 2:4 if you seek it like silver and search for it like hidden treasure,
20Pr 2:5 then you will understand the fear of the LORD and discover the knowledge of God.
20Pr 2:6 For the LORD gives wisdom; from His mouth come knowledge and understanding.
20Pr 2:7 He stores up success for the upright; He is a shield for those who live with integrity
20Pr 2:8 so that He may guard the paths of justice and protect the way of His loyal followers.
20Pr 2:9 Then you will understand righteousness, justice, and integrity-- every good path.
20Pr 2:10 For wisdom will enter your mind, and knowledge will delight your heart.
20Pr 2:11 Discretion will watch over you, and understanding will guard you,
20Pr 2:12 rescuing you from the way of evil-- from the one who says perverse things,
20Pr 2:13 [from] those who abandon the right paths to walk in ways of darkness,
20Pr 2:14 [from] those who enjoy doing evil and celebrate perversity,
20Pr 2:15 whose paths are crooked, and whose ways are devious.
20Pr 2:16 It will rescue you from a forbidden woman, from a stranger with her flattering talk,
20Pr 2:17 who abandons the companion of her youth and forgets the covenant of her God;
20Pr 2:18 for her house sinks down to death and her ways to the land of the departed spirits.
20Pr 2:19 None return who go to her; none reach the paths of life.
20Pr 2:20 So follow the way of good people, and keep to the paths of the righteous.
20Pr 2:21 For the upright will inhabit the land, and those of integrity will remain in it;
20Pr 2:22 but the wicked will be cut off from the land, and the treacherous uprooted from it.
20Pr 3:1 My son, don't forget my teaching, but let your heart keep my commands;
20Pr 3:2 for they will bring you many days, a full life, and well-being.
20Pr 3:3 Never let loyalty and faithfulness leave you. Tie them around your neck; write them on the tablet of your heart.
20Pr 3:4 Then you will find favor and high regard in the sight of God and man.
20Pr 3:5 Trust in the LORD with all your heart, and do not rely on your own understanding;
20Pr 3:6 think about Him in all your ways, and He will guide you on the right paths.
20Pr 3:7 Don't consider yourself to be wise; fear the LORD and turn away from evil.
20Pr 3:8 This will be healing for your body and strengthening for your bones.
20Pr 3:9 Honor the LORD with your possessions and with the first produce of your entire harvest;
20Pr 3:10 then your barns will be completely filled, and your vats will overflow with new wine.
20Pr 3:11 Do not despise the LORD's instruction, my son, and do not loathe His discipline;
20Pr 3:12 for the LORD disciplines the one He loves, just as a father, the son he delights in.
20Pr 3:13 Happy is a man who finds wisdom and who acquires understanding,
20Pr 3:14 for she is more profitable than silver, and her revenue is better than gold.
20Pr 3:15 She is more precious than jewels; nothing you desire compares with her.
20Pr 3:16 Long life is in her right hand; in her left, riches and honor.
20Pr 3:17 Her ways are pleasant, and all her paths, peaceful.
20Pr 3:18 She is a tree of life to those who embrace her, and those who hold on to her are happy.
20Pr 3:19 The LORD founded the earth by wisdom and established the heavens by understanding.
20Pr 3:20 By His knowledge the watery depths broke open, and the clouds dripped with dew.
20Pr 3:21 Maintain [your] competence and discretion. My son, don't lose sight of them.
20Pr 3:22 They will be life for you and adornment for your neck.
20Pr 3:23 Then you will go safely on your way; your foot will not stumble.
20Pr 3:24 When you lie down, you will not be afraid; you will lie down, and your sleep will be pleasant.
20Pr 3:25 Don't fear sudden danger or the ruin of the wicked when it comes,
20Pr 3:26 for the LORD will be your confidence and will keep your foot from a snare.
20Pr 3:27 When it is in your power, don't withhold good from the one to whom it is due.
20Pr 3:28 Don't say to your neighbor, "Go away! Come back later. I'll give it tomorrow"-- when it is there with you.
20Pr 3:29 Don't plan any harm against your neighbor, for he trusts you and lives near you.
20Pr 3:30 Don't accuse anyone without cause, when he has done you no harm.
20Pr 3:31 Don't envy a violent man or choose any of his ways;
20Pr 3:32 for the devious are detestable to the LORD, but He is a friend to the upright.
20Pr 3:33 The LORD's curse is on the household of the wicked, but He blesses the home of the righteous;
20Pr 3:34 He mocks those who mock, but gives grace to the humble.
20Pr 3:35 The wise will inherit honor, but He holds up fools to dishonor.
20Pr 4:1 Listen, [my] sons, to a father's discipline, and pay attention so that you may gain understanding,
20Pr 4:2 for I am giving you good instruction. Don't abandon my teaching.
20Pr 4:3 When I was a son with my father, tender and precious to my mother,
20Pr 4:4 he taught me and said: "Your heart must hold on to my words. Keep my commands and live.
20Pr 4:5 Get wisdom, get understanding; don't forget or turn away from the words of my mouth.
20Pr 4:6 Don't abandon wisdom, and she will watch over you; love her, and she will guard you.
20Pr 4:7 Wisdom is supreme-- so get wisdom. And whatever else you get, get understanding.
20Pr 4:8 Cherish her, and she will exalt you; if you embrace her, she will honor you.
20Pr 4:9 She will place a garland of grace on your head; she will give you a crown of beauty."
20Pr 4:10 Listen, my son. Accept my words, and you will live many years.
20Pr 4:11 I am teaching you the way of wisdom; I am guiding you on straight paths.
20Pr 4:12 When you walk, your steps will not be hindered; when you run, you will not stumble.
20Pr 4:13 Hold on to instruction; don't let go. Guard it, for it is your life.
20Pr 4:14 Don't set foot on the path of the wicked; don't proceed in the way of evil ones.
20Pr 4:15 Avoid it; don't travel on it. Turn away from it, and pass it by.
20Pr 4:16 For they can't sleep unless they have done what is evil; they are robbed of sleep unless they make someone stumble.
20Pr 4:17 They eat the bread of wickedness and drink the wine of violence.
20Pr 4:18 The path of the righteous is like the light of dawn, shining brighter and brighter until midday.
20Pr 4:19 But the way of the wicked is like the darkest gloom; they don't know what makes them stumble.
20Pr 4:20 My son, pay attention to my words; listen closely to my sayings.
20Pr 4:21 Don't lose sight of them; keep them within your heart.
20Pr 4:22 For they are life to those who find them, and health to one's whole body.
20Pr 4:23 Guard your heart above all else, for it is the source of life.
20Pr 4:24 Don't let your mouth speak dishonestly, and don't let your lips talk deviously.
20Pr 4:25 Let your eyes look forward; fix your gaze straight ahead.
20Pr 4:26 Carefully consider the path for your feet, and all your ways will be established.
20Pr 4:27 Don't turn to the right or to the left; keep your feet away from evil.
20Pr 5:1 My son, pay attention to my wisdom; listen closely to my understanding
20Pr 5:2 so that [you] may maintain discretion and your lips safeguard knowledge.
20Pr 5:3 Though the lips of the forbidden woman drip honey and her words are smoother than oil,
20Pr 5:4 in the end she's as bitter as wormwood and as sharp as a double-edged sword.
20Pr 5:5 Her feet go down to death; her steps head straight for Sheol.
20Pr 5:6 She doesn't consider the path of life; she doesn't know that her ways are unstable.
20Pr 5:7 So now, [my] sons, listen to me, and don't turn away from the words of my mouth.
20Pr 5:8 Keep your way far from her. Don't go near the door of her house.
20Pr 5:9 Otherwise, you will give up your vitality to others and your years to someone cruel;
20Pr 5:10 strangers will drain your resources, and your earnings will end up in a foreigner's house.
20Pr 5:11 At the end of your life, you will lament when your physical body has been consumed,
20Pr 5:12 and you will say, "How I hated discipline, and how my heart despised correction.
20Pr 5:13 I didn't obey my teachers or listen closely to my mentors.
20Pr 5:14 I was on the verge of complete ruin before the entire community."
20Pr 5:15 Drink water from your own cistern, water flowing from your own well.
20Pr 5:16 Should your springs flow in the streets, streams of water in the public squares?
20Pr 5:17 They should be for you alone and not for you [to share] with strangers.
20Pr 5:18 Let your fountain be blessed, and take pleasure in the wife of your youth.
20Pr 5:19 A loving doe, a graceful fawn-- let her breasts always satisfy you; be lost in her love forever.
20Pr 5:20 Why, my son, would you be infatuated with a forbidden woman or embrace the breast of a stranger?
20Pr 5:21 For a man's ways are before the LORD's eyes, and He considers all his paths.
20Pr 5:22 A wicked man's iniquities entrap him; he is entangled in the ropes of his own sin.
20Pr 5:23 He will die because there is no instruction, and be lost because of his great stupidity.
20Pr 6:1 My son, if you have put up security for your neighbor or entered into an agreement with a stranger,
20Pr 6:2 you have been trapped by the words of your lips-- ensnared by the words of your mouth.
20Pr 6:3 Do this, then, my son, and free yourself, for you have put yourself in your neighbor's power: Go, humble yourself, and plead with your neighbor.
20Pr 6:4 Don't give sleep to your eyes or slumber to your eyelids.
20Pr 6:5 Escape like a gazelle from a hunter, like a bird from a fowler's trap.
20Pr 6:6 Go to the ant, you slacker! Observe its ways and become wise.
20Pr 6:7 Without leader, administrator, or ruler,
20Pr 6:8 it prepares its provisions in summer; it gathers its food during harvest.
20Pr 6:9 How long will you stay in bed, you slacker? When will you get up from your sleep?
20Pr 6:10 A little sleep, a little slumber, a little folding of the arms to rest,
20Pr 6:11 and your poverty will come like a robber, your need, like a bandit.
20Pr 6:12 A worthless person, a wicked man, who goes around speaking dishonestly,
20Pr 6:13 who winks his eyes, signals with his feet, and gestures with his fingers,
20Pr 6:14 who plots evil with perversity in his heart-- he stirs up trouble constantly.
20Pr 6:15 Therefore calamity will strike him suddenly; he will be shattered instantly-- beyond recovery.
20Pr 6:16 Six things the LORD hates; in fact, seven are detestable to Him:
20Pr 6:17 arrogant eyes, a lying tongue, hands that shed innocent blood,
20Pr 6:18 a heart that plots wicked schemes, feet eager to run to evil,
20Pr 6:19 a lying witness who gives false testimony, and one who stirs up trouble among brothers.
20Pr 6:20 My son, keep your father's command, and don't reject your mother's teaching.
20Pr 6:21 Always bind them to your heart; tie them around your neck.
20Pr 6:22 When you walk here and there, they will guide you; when you lie down, they will watch over you; when you wake up, they will talk to you.
20Pr 6:23 For a commandment is a lamp, teaching is a light, and corrective instructions are the way to life.
20Pr 6:24 They will protect you from an evil woman, from the flattering tongue of a stranger.
20Pr 6:25 Don't lust in your heart for her beauty or let her captivate you with her eyelashes.
20Pr 6:26 For a prostitute's fee is only a loaf of bread, but an adulteress goes after [your] very life.
20Pr 6:27 Can a man embrace fire and his clothes not be burned?
20Pr 6:28 Can a man walk on coals without scorching his feet?
20Pr 6:29 So it is with the one who sleeps with another man's wife; no one who touches her will go unpunished.
20Pr 6:30 People don't despise the thief if he steals to satisfy himself when he is hungry.
20Pr 6:31 Still, if caught, he must pay seven times as much; he must give up all the wealth in his house.
20Pr 6:32 The one who commits adultery lacks sense; whoever does so destroys himself.
20Pr 6:33 He will get a beating and dishonor, and his disgrace will never be removed.
20Pr 6:34 For jealousy enrages a husband, and he will show no mercy when he takes revenge.
20Pr 6:35 He will not be appeased by anything or be persuaded by lavish gifts.
20Pr 7:1 My son, obey my words, and treasure my commands.
20Pr 7:2 Keep my commands and live; protect my teachings as you would the pupil of your eye.
20Pr 7:3 Tie them to your fingers; write them on the tablet of your heart.
20Pr 7:4 Say to wisdom, "You are my sister," and call understanding [your] relative.
20Pr 7:5 She will keep you from a forbidden woman, a stranger with her flattering talk.
20Pr 7:6 At the window of my house I looked through my lattice.
20Pr 7:7 I saw among the inexperienced, I noticed among the youths, a young man lacking sense.
20Pr 7:8 Crossing the street near her corner, he strolled down the road to her house
20Pr 7:9 at twilight, in the evening, in the dark of the night.
20Pr 7:10 A woman came to meet him, dressed like a prostitute, having a hidden agenda.
20Pr 7:11 She is loud and defiant; her feet do not stay at home.
20Pr 7:12 Now in the street, now in the squares, she lurks at every corner.
20Pr 7:13 She grabs him and kisses him; she brazenly says to him,
20Pr 7:14 "I've made fellowship offerings; today I've fulfilled my vows.
20Pr 7:15 So I came out to meet you, to search for you, and I've found you.
20Pr 7:16 I've spread coverings on my bed-- richly colored linen from Egypt.
20Pr 7:17 I've perfumed my bed with myrrh, aloes, and cinnamon.
20Pr 7:18 Come, let's drink deeply of lovemaking until morning. Let's feast on each other's love!
20Pr 7:19 My husband isn't home; he went on a long journey.
20Pr 7:20 He took a bag of money with him and will come home at the time of the full moon."
20Pr 7:21 She seduces him with her persistent pleading; she lures with her flattering talk.
20Pr 7:22 He follows her impulsively like an ox going to the slaughter, like a deer bounding toward a trap
20Pr 7:23 until an arrow pierces its liver, like a bird darting into a snare-- he doesn't know it will cost him his life.
20Pr 7:24 Now, [my] sons, listen to me, and pay attention to the words of my mouth.
20Pr 7:25 Don't let your heart turn aside to her ways; don't stray onto her paths.
20Pr 7:26 For she has brought many down to death; her victims are countless.
20Pr 7:27 Her house is the road to Sheol, descending to the chambers of death.
20Pr 8:1 Doesn't Wisdom call out? Doesn't Understanding make her voice heard?
20Pr 8:2 At the heights overlooking the road, at the crossroads, she takes her stand.
20Pr 8:3 Beside the gates at the entry to the city, at the main entrance, she cries out:
20Pr 8:4 "People, I call out to you; my cry is to mankind.
20Pr 8:5 Learn to be shrewd, you who are inexperienced; develop common sense, you who are foolish.
20Pr 8:6 Listen, for I speak of noble things, and what my lips say is right.
20Pr 8:7 For my mouth tells the truth, and wickedness is detestable to my lips.
20Pr 8:8 All the words of my mouth are righteous; none of them are deceptive or perverse.
20Pr 8:9 All of them are clear to the perceptive, and right to those who discover knowledge.
20Pr 8:10 Accept my instruction instead of silver, and knowledge rather than pure gold.
20Pr 8:11 For wisdom is better than precious stones, and nothing desirable can compare with it.
20Pr 8:12 I, Wisdom, share a home with shrewdness and have knowledge and discretion.
20Pr 8:13 To fear the LORD is to hate evil. I hate arrogant pride, evil conduct, and perverse speech.
20Pr 8:14 I possess good advice and competence; I have understanding and strength.
20Pr 8:15 It is by me that kings reign and rulers enact just law;
20Pr 8:16 by me, princes lead, as do nobles [and] all righteous judges.
20Pr 8:17 I love those who love me, and those who search for me find me.
20Pr 8:18 With me are riches and honor, lasting wealth and righteousness.
20Pr 8:19 My fruit is better than solid gold, and my harvest than pure silver.
20Pr 8:20 I walk in the way of righteousness, along the paths of justice,
20Pr 8:21 giving wealth as an inheritance to those who love me, and filling their treasuries.
20Pr 8:22 The LORD made me at the beginning of His creation, before His works of long ago.
20Pr 8:23 I was formed before ancient times, from the beginning, before the earth began.
20Pr 8:24 I was brought forth when there were no watery depths and no springs filled with water.
20Pr 8:25 I was brought forth before the mountains and hills were established,
20Pr 8:26 before He made the land, the fields, or the first soil on earth.
20Pr 8:27 I was there when He established the heavens, when He laid out the horizon on the surface of the ocean,
20Pr 8:28 when He placed the skies above, when the fountains of the ocean gushed forth,
20Pr 8:29 when He set a limit for the sea so that the waters would not violate His command, when He laid out the foundations of the earth.
20Pr 8:30 I was a skilled craftsman beside Him. I was His delight every day, always rejoicing before Him.
20Pr 8:31 I was rejoicing in His inhabited world, delighting in the human race.
20Pr 8:32 And now, [my] sons, listen to me; those who keep my ways are happy.
20Pr 8:33 Listen to instruction and be wise; don't ignore it.
20Pr 8:34 Anyone who listens to me is happy, watching at my doors every day, waiting by the posts of my doorway.
20Pr 8:35 For the one who finds me finds life and obtains favor from the LORD,
20Pr 8:36 but the one who sins against me harms himself; all who hate me love death."
20Pr 9:1 Wisdom has built her house; she has carved out her seven pillars.
20Pr 9:2 She has prepared her meat; she has mixed her wine; she has also set her table.
20Pr 9:3 She has sent out her servants; she calls out from the highest points of the city:
20Pr 9:4 "Whoever is inexperienced, enter here!" To the one who lacks sense, she says,
20Pr 9:5 "Come, eat my bread, and drink the wine I have mixed.
20Pr 9:6 Leave inexperience behind, and you will live; pursue the way of understanding.
20Pr 9:7 The one who corrects a mocker will bring dishonor on himself; the one who rebukes a wicked man will get hurt.
20Pr 9:8 Don't rebuke a mocker, or he will hate you; rebuke a wise man, and he will love you.
20Pr 9:9 Instruct a wise man, and he will be wiser still; teach a righteous man, and he will learn more.
20Pr 9:10 The fear of the LORD is the beginning of wisdom, and the knowledge of the Holy One is understanding.
20Pr 9:11 For by Wisdom your days will be many, and years will be added to your life.
20Pr 9:12 If you are wise, you are wise for your own benefit; if you mock, you alone will bear [the consequences]."
20Pr 9:13 The woman Folly is rowdy; she is gullible and knows nothing.
20Pr 9:14 She sits by the doorway of her house, on a seat at the highest point of the city,
20Pr 9:15 calling to those who pass by, who go straight ahead on their paths:
20Pr 9:16 "Whoever is inexperienced, enter here!" To the one who lacks sense, she says,
20Pr 9:17 "Stolen water is sweet, and bread [eaten] secretly is tasty!"
20Pr 9:18 But he doesn't know that the departed spirits are there, that her guests are in the depths of Sheol.
20Pr 10:1 Solomon's proverbs: A wise son brings joy to his father, but a foolish son, heartache to his mother.
20Pr 10:2 Ill-gotten gains do not profit anyone, but righteousness rescues from death.
20Pr 10:3 The LORD will not let the righteous go hungry, but He denies the wicked what they crave.
20Pr 10:4 Idle hands make one poor, but diligent hands bring riches.
20Pr 10:5 The son who gathers during summer is prudent; the son who sleeps during harvest is disgraceful.
20Pr 10:6 Blessings are on the head of the righteous, but the mouth of the wicked conceals violence.
20Pr 10:7 The remembrance of the righteous is a blessing, but the name of the wicked will rot.
20Pr 10:8 A wise heart accepts commands, but foolish lips will be destroyed.
20Pr 10:9 The one who lives with integrity lives securely, but whoever perverts his ways will be found out.
20Pr 10:10 A sly wink of the eye causes grief, and foolish lips will be destroyed.
20Pr 10:11 The mouth of the righteous is a fountain of life, but the mouth of the wicked conceals violence.
20Pr 10:12 Hatred stirs up conflicts, but love covers all offenses.
20Pr 10:13 Wisdom is found on the lips of the discerning, but a rod is for the back of the one who lacks sense.
20Pr 10:14 The wise store up knowledge, but the mouth of the fool hastens destruction.
20Pr 10:15 A rich man's wealth is his fortified city; the poverty of the poor is their destruction.
20Pr 10:16 The labor of the righteous leads to life; the activity of the wicked leads to sin.
20Pr 10:17 The one who follows instruction is on the path to life, but the one who rejects correction goes astray.
20Pr 10:18 The one who conceals hatred has lying lips, and whoever spreads slander is a fool.
20Pr 10:19 When there are many words, sin is unavoidable, but the one who controls his lips is wise.
20Pr 10:20 The tongue of the righteous is pure silver; the heart of the wicked is of little value.
20Pr 10:21 The lips of the righteous feed many, but fools die for lack of sense.
20Pr 10:22 The LORD's blessing enriches, and struggle adds nothing to it.
20Pr 10:23 As shameful conduct is pleasure for a fool, so wisdom is for a man of understanding.
20Pr 10:24 What the wicked dreads will come to him, but what the righteous desires will be given to him.
20Pr 10:25 When the whirlwind passes, the wicked are no more, but the righteous are secure forever.
20Pr 10:26 Like vinegar to the teeth and smoke to the eyes, so the slacker is to the one who sends him [on an errand].
20Pr 10:27 The fear of the LORD prolongs life, but the years of the wicked are cut short.
20Pr 10:28 The hope of the righteous is joy, but the expectation of the wicked comes to nothing.
20Pr 10:29 The way of the LORD is a stronghold for the honorable, but destruction awaits the malicious.
20Pr 10:30 The righteous will never be shaken, but the wicked will not remain on the earth.
20Pr 10:31 The mouth of the righteous produces wisdom, but a perverse tongue will be cut out.
20Pr 10:32 The lips of the righteous know what is appropriate, but the mouth of the wicked, [only] what is perverse.
20Pr 11:1 Dishonest scales are detestable to the LORD, but an accurate weight is His delight.
20Pr 11:2 When pride comes, disgrace follows, but with humility comes wisdom.
20Pr 11:3 The integrity of the upright guides them, but the perversity of the treacherous destroys them.
20Pr 11:4 Wealth is not profitable on a day of wrath, but righteousness rescues from death.
20Pr 11:5 The righteousness of the blameless clears his path, but the wicked person will fall because of his wickedness.
20Pr 11:6 The righteousness of the upright rescues them, but the treacherous are trapped by their own desires.
20Pr 11:7 When the wicked dies, his expectation comes to nothing, and hope placed in wealth vanishes.
20Pr 11:8 The righteous is rescued from trouble; in his place, the wicked goes in.
20Pr 11:9 With his mouth the ungodly destroys his neighbor, but through knowledge the righteous are rescued.
20Pr 11:10 When the righteous thrive, a city rejoices, and when the wicked die, there is joyful shouting.
20Pr 11:11 A city is built up by the blessing of the upright, but it is torn down by the mouth of the wicked.
20Pr 11:12 Whoever shows contempt for his neighbor lacks sense, but a man with understanding keeps silent.
20Pr 11:13 A gossip goes around revealing a secret, but the trustworthy keeps a confidence.
20Pr 11:14 Without guidance, people fall, but with many counselors there is deliverance.
20Pr 11:15 If someone puts up security for a stranger, he will suffer for it, but the one who hates such agreements is protected.
20Pr 11:16 A gracious woman gains honor, but violent men gain [only] riches.
20Pr 11:17 A kind man benefits himself, but a cruel man brings disaster on himself.
20Pr 11:18 The wicked man earns an empty wage, but the one who sows righteousness, a true reward.
20Pr 11:19 Genuine righteousness [leads] to life, but pursuing evil [leads] to death.
20Pr 11:20 Those with twisted minds are detestable to the LORD, but those with blameless conduct are His delight.
20Pr 11:21 Be assured that the wicked will not go unpunished, but the offspring of the righteous will escape.
20Pr 11:22 A beautiful woman who rejects good sense is like a gold ring in a pig's snout.
20Pr 11:23 The desire of the righteous [turns out] well, but the hope of the wicked [leads to] wrath.
20Pr 11:24 One person gives freely, yet gains more; another withholds what is right, only to become poor.
20Pr 11:25 A generous person will be enriched, and the one who gives a drink of water will receive water.
20Pr 11:26 People will curse anyone who hoards grain, but a blessing will come to the one who sells it.
20Pr 11:27 The one who searches for what is good finds favor, but if someone looks for trouble, it will come to him.
20Pr 11:28 Anyone trusting in his riches will fall, but the righteous will flourish like foliage.
20Pr 11:29 The one who brings ruin on his household will inherit the wind, and a fool will be a slave to someone whose heart is wise.
20Pr 11:30 The fruit of the righteous is a tree of life, but violence takes lives.
20Pr 11:31 If the righteous will be repaid on earth, how much more the wicked and sinful.
20Pr 12:1 Whoever loves instruction loves knowledge, but one who hates correction is stupid.
20Pr 12:2 The good obtain favor from the LORD, but He condemns a man who schemes.
20Pr 12:3 Man cannot be made secure by wickedness, but the root of the righteous is immovable.
20Pr 12:4 A capable wife is her husband's crown, but a wife who causes shame is like rottenness in his bones.
20Pr 12:5 The thoughts of the righteous [are] just, but guidance from the wicked [leads to] deceit.
20Pr 12:6 The words of the wicked are a deadly ambush, but the speech of the upright rescues them.
20Pr 12:7 The wicked are overthrown and perish, but the house of the righteous will stand.
20Pr 12:8 A man is praised for his insight, but a twisted mind is despised.
20Pr 12:9 Better to be dishonored, yet have a servant, than to act important but have no food.
20Pr 12:10 A righteous man cares about his animal's health, but [even] the merciful acts of the wicked are cruel.
20Pr 12:11 The one who works his land will have plenty of food, but whoever chases fantasies lacks sense.
20Pr 12:12 The wicked desire what evil men have, but the root of the righteous produces [fruit].
20Pr 12:13 An evil man is trapped by [his] rebellious speech, but the righteous escapes from trouble.
20Pr 12:14 A man will be satisfied with good by the words of his mouth, and the work of a man's hands will reward him.
20Pr 12:15 A fool's way is right in his own eyes, but whoever listens to counsel is wise.
20Pr 12:16 A fool's displeasure is known at once, but whoever ignores an insult is sensible.
20Pr 12:17 Whoever speaks the truth declares what is right, but a false witness, deceit.
20Pr 12:18 There is one who speaks rashly, like a piercing sword; but the tongue of the wise [brings] healing.
20Pr 12:19 Truthful lips endure forever, but a lying tongue, only a moment.
20Pr 12:20 Deceit is in the hearts of those who plot evil, but those who promote peace have joy.
20Pr 12:21 No disaster [overcomes] the righteous, but the wicked are full of misery.
20Pr 12:22 Lying lips are detestable to the LORD, but faithful people are His delight.
20Pr 12:23 A shrewd person conceals knowledge, but a foolish heart publicizes stupidity.
20Pr 12:24 The diligent hand will rule, but laziness will lead to forced labor.
20Pr 12:25 Anxiety in a man's heart weighs it down, but a good word cheers it up.
20Pr 12:26 A righteous man is careful in dealing with his neighbor, but the ways of wicked men lead them astray.
20Pr 12:27 A lazy man doesn't roast his game, but to a diligent man, his wealth is precious.
20Pr 12:28 There is life in the path of righteousness, but another path leads to death.
20Pr 13:1 A wise son [hears his] father's instruction, but a mocker doesn't listen to rebuke.
20Pr 13:2 From the words of his mouth, a man will enjoy good things, but treacherous people have an appetite for violence.
20Pr 13:3 The one who guards his mouth protects his life; the one who opens his lips invites his own ruin.
20Pr 13:4 The slacker craves, yet has nothing, but the diligent is fully satisfied.
20Pr 13:5 The righteous hate lying, but the wicked act disgustingly and disgracefully.
20Pr 13:6 Righteousness guards people of integrity, but wickedness undermines the sinner.
20Pr 13:7 One man pretends to be rich but has nothing; another pretends to be poor but has great wealth.
20Pr 13:8 Riches are a ransom for a man's life, but a poor man hears no threat.
20Pr 13:9 The light of the righteous shines brightly, but the lamp of the wicked is extinguished.
20Pr 13:10 Arrogance leads to nothing but strife, but wisdom is gained by those who take advice.
20Pr 13:11 Wealth obtained by fraud will dwindle, but whoever earns it through labor will multiply it.
20Pr 13:12 Delayed hope makes the heart sick, but fulfilled desire is a tree of life.
20Pr 13:13 The one who has contempt for instruction will pay the penalty, but the one who respects a command will be rewarded.
20Pr 13:14 A wise man's instruction is a fountain of life, turning people away from the snares of death.
20Pr 13:15 Good sense wins favor, but the way of the treacherous never changes.
20Pr 13:16 Every sensible person acts knowledgeably, but a fool displays his stupidity.
20Pr 13:17 A wicked messenger falls into trouble, but a trustworthy courier [brings] healing.
20Pr 13:18 Poverty and disgrace [come to] those who ignore instruction, but the one who accepts rebuke will be honored.
20Pr 13:19 Desire fulfilled is sweet to the taste, but fools hate to turn from evil.
20Pr 13:20 The one who walks with the wise will become wise, but a companion of fools will suffer harm.
20Pr 13:21 Disaster pursues sinners, but good rewards the righteous.
20Pr 13:22 A good man leaves an inheritance to his grandchildren, but the sinner's wealth is stored up for the righteous.
20Pr 13:23 The field of the poor yields abundant food, but without justice, it is swept away.
20Pr 13:24 The one who will not use the rod hates his son, but the one who loves him disciplines him diligently.
20Pr 13:25 A righteous man eats until he is satisfied, but the stomach of the wicked is empty.
20Pr 14:1 Every wise woman builds her house, but a foolish one tears it down with her own hands.
20Pr 14:2 Whoever lives with integrity fears the LORD, but the one who is devious in his ways despises Him.
20Pr 14:3 The proud speech of a fool [brings] a rod [of discipline], but the lips of the wise protect them.
20Pr 14:4 Where there are no oxen, the feeding-trough is empty, but an abundant harvest [comes] through the strength of an ox.
20Pr 14:5 An honest witness does not deceive, but a dishonest witness utters lies.
20Pr 14:6 A mocker seeks wisdom and doesn't find it, but knowledge [comes] easily to the perceptive.
20Pr 14:7 Stay away from a foolish man; you will gain no knowledge from his speech.
20Pr 14:8 The sensible man's wisdom is to consider his way, but the stupidity of fools deceives [them].
20Pr 14:9 Fools mock at making restitution, but there is goodwill among the upright.
20Pr 14:10 The heart knows its own bitterness, and no outsider shares in its joy.
20Pr 14:11 The house of the wicked will be destroyed, but the tent of the upright will stand.
20Pr 14:12 There is a way that seems right to a man, but its end is the way to death.
20Pr 14:13 Even in laughter a heart may be sad, and joy may end in grief.
20Pr 14:14 The disloyal will get what their conduct deserves, and a good man, what his [deeds deserve.]
20Pr 14:15 The inexperienced believe anything, but the sensible watch their steps.
20Pr 14:16 A wise man is cautious and turns from evil, but a fool is easily angered and is careless.
20Pr 14:17 A quick-tempered man acts foolishly, and a man who schemes is hated.
20Pr 14:18 The gullible inherit foolishness, but the sensible are crowned with knowledge.
20Pr 14:19 The evil bow before those who are good, the wicked, at the gates of the righteous.
20Pr 14:20 A poor man is hated even by his neighbor, but there are many who love the rich.
20Pr 14:21 The one who despises his neighbor sins, but whoever shows kindness to the poor will be happy.
20Pr 14:22 Don't those who plan evil go astray? But those who plan good find loyalty and faithfulness.
20Pr 14:23 There is profit in all hard work, but endless talk leads only to poverty.
20Pr 14:24 The crown of the wise is their wealth, but the foolishness of fools produces foolishness.
20Pr 14:25 A truthful witness rescues lives, but one who utters lies is deceitful.
20Pr 14:26 In the fear of the LORD one has strong confidence and his children have a refuge.
20Pr 14:27 The fear of the LORD is a fountain of life, turning people from the snares of death.
20Pr 14:28 A large population is a king's splendor, but a shortage of people is a ruler's devastation.
20Pr 14:29 A patient person [shows] great understanding, but a quick-tempered one promotes foolishness.
20Pr 14:30 A tranquil heart is life to the body, but jealousy is rottenness to the bones.
20Pr 14:31 The one who oppresses the poor insults their Maker, but one who is kind to the needy honors Him.
20Pr 14:32 The wicked are thrown down by their own sin, but the righteous have a refuge when they die.
20Pr 14:33 Wisdom resides in the heart of the discerning; she is known even among fools.
20Pr 14:34 Righteousness exalts a nation, but sin is a disgrace to any people.
20Pr 14:35 A king favors a wise servant, but his anger falls on a disgraceful one.
20Pr 15:1 A gentle answer turns away anger, but a harsh word stirs up wrath.
20Pr 15:2 The tongue of the wise makes knowledge attractive, but the mouth of fools blurts out foolishness.
20Pr 15:3 The eyes of the LORD are everywhere, observing the wicked and the good.
20Pr 15:4 The tongue that heals is a tree of life, but a devious tongue breaks the spirit.
20Pr 15:5 A fool despises his father's instruction, but a person who heeds correction is sensible.
20Pr 15:6 The house of the righteous has great wealth, but trouble accompanies the income of the wicked.
20Pr 15:7 The lips of the wise broadcast knowledge, but not so the heart of fools.
20Pr 15:8 The sacrifice of the wicked is detestable to the LORD, but the prayer of the upright is His delight.
20Pr 15:9 The LORD detests the way of the wicked, but He loves the one who pursues righteousness.
20Pr 15:10 Discipline is harsh for the one who leaves the path; the one who hates correction will die.
20Pr 15:11 Sheol and Abaddon lie open before the LORD-- how much more, human hearts.
20Pr 15:12 A mocker doesn't love one who corrects him; he will not consult the wise.
20Pr 15:13 A joyful heart makes a face cheerful, but a sad heart [produces] a broken spirit.
20Pr 15:14 A discerning mind seeks knowledge, but the mouth of fools feeds on foolishness.
20Pr 15:15 All the days of the oppressed are miserable, but a cheerful heart has a continual feast.
20Pr 15:16 Better a little with the fear of the LORD than great treasure with turmoil.
20Pr 15:17 Better a meal of vegetables where there is love than a fattened calf with hatred.
20Pr 15:18 A hot-tempered man stirs up conflict, but a man slow to anger calms strife.
20Pr 15:19 A slacker's way is like a thorny hedge, but the path of the upright is a highway.
20Pr 15:20 A wise son brings joy to his father, but a foolish one despises his mother.
20Pr 15:21 Foolishness brings joy to one without sense, but a man with understanding walks a straight path.
20Pr 15:22 Plans fail when there is no counsel, but with many advisers they succeed.
20Pr 15:23 A man takes joy in giving an answer; and a timely word-- how good that is!
20Pr 15:24 For the discerning the path of life leads upward, so that he may avoid going down to Sheol.
20Pr 15:25 The LORD destroys the house of the proud, but He protects the widow's territory.
20Pr 15:26 The LORD detests the plans of an evil man, but pleasant words are pure.
20Pr 15:27 The one who profits dishonestly troubles his household, but the one who hates bribes will live.
20Pr 15:28 The mind of the righteous person thinks before answering, but the mouth of the wicked blurts out evil things.
20Pr 15:29 The LORD is far from the wicked, but He hears the prayer of the righteous.
20Pr 15:30 Bright eyes cheer the heart; good news strengthens the bones.
20Pr 15:31 An ear that listens to life-giving rebukes will be at home among the wise.
20Pr 15:32 Anyone who ignores instruction despises himself, but whoever listens to correction acquires good sense.
20Pr 15:33 The fear of the LORD is wisdom's instruction, and humility comes before honor.
20Pr 16:1 The reflections of the heart belong to man, but the answer of the tongue is from the LORD.
20Pr 16:2 All a man's ways seem right in his own eyes, but the LORD weighs the motives.
20Pr 16:3 Commit your activities to the LORD and your plans will be achieved.
20Pr 16:4 The LORD has prepared everything for His purpose-- even the wicked for the day of disaster.
20Pr 16:5 Everyone with a proud heart is detestable to the LORD; be assured, he will not go unpunished.
20Pr 16:6 Wickedness is atoned for by loyalty and faithfulness, and one turns from evil by the fear of the LORD.
20Pr 16:7 When a man's ways please the LORD, He makes even his enemies to be at peace with him.
20Pr 16:8 Better a little with righteousness than great income with injustice.
20Pr 16:9 A man's heart plans his way, but the LORD determines his steps.
20Pr 16:10 God's verdict is on the lips of a king; his mouth should not err in judgment.
20Pr 16:11 Honest balances and scales are the LORD's; all the weights in the bag are His concern.
20Pr 16:12 Wicked behavior is detestable to kings, since a throne is established through righteousness.
20Pr 16:13 Righteous lips are a king's delight, and he loves one who speaks honestly.
20Pr 16:14 A king's fury is a messenger of death, but a wise man appeases it.
20Pr 16:15 When a king's face lights up, there is life; his favor is like a cloud with spring rain.
20Pr 16:16 Acquire wisdom-- how much better it is than gold! And acquire understanding-- it is preferable to silver.
20Pr 16:17 The highway of the upright avoids evil; the one who guards his way protects his life.
20Pr 16:18 Pride comes before destruction, and an arrogant spirit before a fall.
20Pr 16:19 Better to be lowly of spirit with the humble than to divide plunder with the proud.
20Pr 16:20 The one who understands a matter finds success, and the one who trusts in the LORD will be happy.
20Pr 16:21 Anyone with a wise heart is called discerning, and pleasant speech increases learning.
20Pr 16:22 Insight is a fountain of life for its possessor, but folly is the instruction of fools.
20Pr 16:23 A wise heart instructs its mouth and increases learning with its speech.
20Pr 16:24 Pleasant words are a honeycomb: sweet to the taste and health to the body.
20Pr 16:25 There is a way that seems right to a man, but in the end it is the way of death.
20Pr 16:26 A worker's appetite works for him because his hunger urges him on.
20Pr 16:27 A worthless man digs up evil, and his speech is like a scorching fire.
20Pr 16:28 A contrary man spreads conflict, and a gossip separates friends.
20Pr 16:29 A violent man lures his neighbor, leading him in a way that is not good.
20Pr 16:30 The one who narrows his eyes is planning deceptions; the one who compresses his lips brings about evil.
20Pr 16:31 Gray hair is a glorious crown; it is found in the way of righteousness.
20Pr 16:32 Patience is better than power, and controlling one's temper, than capturing a city.
20Pr 16:33 The lot is cast into the lap, but its every decision is from the LORD.
20Pr 17:1 Better a dry crust with peace than a house full of feasting with strife.
20Pr 17:2 A wise servant will rule over a disgraceful son and share an inheritance among brothers.
20Pr 17:3 A crucible is for silver and a smelter for gold, but the LORD is a tester of hearts.
20Pr 17:4 A wicked person listens to malicious talk; a liar pays attention to a destructive tongue.
20Pr 17:5 The one who mocks the poor insults his Maker, and one who rejoices over disaster will not go unpunished.
20Pr 17:6 Grandchildren are the crown of the elderly, and the pride of sons is their fathers.
20Pr 17:7 Excessive speech is not appropriate on a fool's lips; how much worse are lies for a ruler.
20Pr 17:8 A bribe seems like a magic stone to its owner; wherever he turns, he succeeds.
20Pr 17:9 Whoever conceals an offense promotes love, but whoever gossips about it separates friends.
20Pr 17:10 A rebuke cuts into a perceptive person more than a hundred lashes into a fool.
20Pr 17:11 An evil man seeks only rebellion; a cruel messenger will be sent against him.
20Pr 17:12 Better for a man to meet a bear robbed of her cubs than a fool in his foolishness.
20Pr 17:13 If anyone returns evil for good, evil will never depart from his house.
20Pr 17:14 To start a conflict is to release a flood; stop the dispute before it breaks out.
20Pr 17:15 Acquitting the guilty and condemning the just-- both are detestable to the LORD.
20Pr 17:16 Why does a fool have money in his hand with no intention of buying wisdom?
20Pr 17:17 A friend loves at all times, and a brother is born for a difficult time.
20Pr 17:18 One without sense enters an agreement and puts up security for his friend.
20Pr 17:19 One who loves to offend loves strife; one who builds a high threshold invites injury.
20Pr 17:20 One with a twisted mind will not succeed, and one with deceitful speech will fall into ruin.
20Pr 17:21 A man fathers a fool to his own sorrow; the father of a fool has no joy.
20Pr 17:22 A joyful heart is good medicine, but a broken spirit dries up the bones.
20Pr 17:23 A wicked man secretly takes a bribe to subvert the course of justice.
20Pr 17:24 Wisdom is the focus of the perceptive, but a fool's eyes roam to the ends of the earth.
20Pr 17:25 A foolish son is grief to his father and bitterness to the one who bore him.
20Pr 17:26 It is certainly not good to fine an innocent person, or to beat a noble for his honesty.
20Pr 17:27 The intelligent person restrains his words, and one who keeps a cool head is a man of understanding.
20Pr 17:28 Even a fool is considered wise when he keeps silent, discerning, when he seals his lips.
20Pr 18:1 One who isolates himself pursues [selfish] desires; he rebels against all sound judgment.
20Pr 18:2 A fool does not delight in understanding, but only wants to show off his opinions.
20Pr 18:3 When a wicked man comes, shame does also, and along with dishonor, disgrace.
20Pr 18:4 The words of a man's mouth are deep waters, a flowing river, a fountain of wisdom.
20Pr 18:5 It is not good to show partiality to the guilty by perverting the justice due the innocent.
20Pr 18:6 A fool's lips lead to strife, and his mouth provokes a beating.
20Pr 18:7 A fool's mouth is his devastation, and his lips are a trap for his life.
20Pr 18:8 A gossip's words are like choice food that goes down to one's innermost being.
20Pr 18:9 The one who is truly lazy in his work is brother to a vandal.
20Pr 18:10 The name of the LORD is a strong tower; the righteous run to it and are protected.
20Pr 18:11 A rich man's wealth is his fortified city; in his imagination it is like a high wall.
20Pr 18:12 Before his downfall a man's heart is proud, but before honor comes humility.
20Pr 18:13 The one who gives an answer before he listens-- this is foolishness and disgrace for him.
20Pr 18:14 A man's spirit can endure sickness, but who can survive a broken spirit?
20Pr 18:15 The mind of the discerning acquires knowledge, and the ear of the wise seeks it.
20Pr 18:16 A gift opens doors for a man and brings him before the great.
20Pr 18:17 The first to state his case seems right until another comes and cross-examines him.
20Pr 18:18 [Casting] the lot ends quarrels and separates powerful opponents.
20Pr 18:19 An offended brother is [harder to reach] than a fortified city, and quarrels are like the bars of a fortress.
20Pr 18:20 From the fruit of his mouth a man's stomach is satisfied; he is filled with the product of his lips.
20Pr 18:21 Life and death are in the power of the tongue, and those who love it will eat its fruit.
20Pr 18:22 A man who finds a wife finds a good thing and obtains favor from the LORD.
20Pr 18:23 The poor man pleads, but the rich one answers roughly.
20Pr 18:24 A man with many friends may be harmed, but there is a friend who stays closer than a brother.
20Pr 19:1 Better a poor man who walks in integrity than someone who has deceitful lips and is a fool.
20Pr 19:2 Even zeal is not good without knowledge, and the one who acts hastily sins.
20Pr 19:3 A man's own foolishness leads him astray, yet his heart rages against the LORD.
20Pr 19:4 Wealth attracts many friends, but a poor man is separated from his friend.
20Pr 19:5 A false witness will not go unpunished, and one who utters lies will not escape.
20Pr 19:6 Many seek the favor of a ruler, and everyone is a friend of one who gives gifts.
20Pr 19:7 All the brothers of a poor man hate him; how much more do his friends keep their distance from him! He may pursue [them with] words, [but] they are not [there].
20Pr 19:8 The one who acquires good sense loves himself; one who safeguards understanding finds success.
20Pr 19:9 A false witness will not go unpunished, and one who utters lies perishes.
20Pr 19:10 Luxury is not appropriate for a fool-- how much less for a slave to rule over princes!
20Pr 19:11 A person's insight gives him patience, and his virtue is to overlook an offense.
20Pr 19:12 A king's rage is like a lion's roar, but his favor is like dew on the grass.
20Pr 19:13 A foolish son is his father's ruin, and a wife's nagging is an endless dripping.
20Pr 19:14 A house and wealth are inherited from fathers, but a sensible wife is from the LORD.
20Pr 19:15 Laziness induces deep sleep, and a lazy person will go hungry.
20Pr 19:16 The one who keeps commands preserves himself; one who disregards his ways will die.
20Pr 19:17 Kindness to the poor is a loan to the LORD, and He will give a reward to the lender.
20Pr 19:18 Discipline your son while there is hope; don't be intent on killing him.
20Pr 19:19 A person with great anger bears the penalty; if you rescue him, you'll have to do it again.
20Pr 19:20 Listen to counsel and receive instruction so that you may be wise in later life.
20Pr 19:21 Many plans are in a man's heart, but the LORD's decree will prevail.
20Pr 19:22 A man's desire should be loyalty to the covenant; better to be a poor man than a perjurer.
20Pr 19:23 The fear of the LORD leads to life; one will sleep at night without danger.
20Pr 19:24 The slacker buries his hand in the bowl; he doesn't even bring it back to his mouth.
20Pr 19:25 Strike a mocker, and the inexperienced learn a lesson; rebuke the discerning, and he gains knowledge.
20Pr 19:26 The one who assaults his father and evicts his mother is a disgraceful and shameful son.
20Pr 19:27 If you stop listening to instruction, my son, you will stray from the words of knowledge.
20Pr 19:28 A worthless witness mocks justice, and a wicked mouth swallows iniquity.
20Pr 19:29 Judgments are prepared for mockers, and beatings for the backs of fools.
20Pr 20:1 Wine is a mocker, beer is a brawler, and whoever staggers because of them is not wise.
20Pr 20:2 A king's terrible wrath is like the roaring of a lion; anyone who provokes him endangers himself.
20Pr 20:3 It is honorable for a man to resolve a dispute, but any fool can get himself into a quarrel.
20Pr 20:4 The slacker does not plow during planting season; at harvest time he looks, and there is nothing.
20Pr 20:5 Counsel in a man's heart is deep water; but a man of understanding draws it up.
20Pr 20:6 Many a man proclaims his own loyalty, but who can find a trustworthy man?
20Pr 20:7 The one who lives with integrity is righteous; his children who come after him will be happy.
20Pr 20:8 A king sitting on a throne to judge sifts out all evil with his eyes.
20Pr 20:9 Who can say, "I have kept my heart pure; I am cleansed from my sin"?
20Pr 20:10 Differing weights and varying measures-- both are detestable to the LORD.
20Pr 20:11 Even a young man is known by his actions-- by whether his behavior is pure and upright.
20Pr 20:12 The hearing ear and the seeing eye-- the LORD made them both.
20Pr 20:13 Don't love sleep, or you will become poor; open your eyes, and you'll have enough to eat.
20Pr 20:14 "It's worthless, it's worthless!" the buyer says, but after he is on his way, he gloats.
20Pr 20:15 There is gold and a multitude of jewels, but knowledgeable lips are a rare treasure.
20Pr 20:16 Take his garment, for he has put up security for a stranger; get collateral if it is for foreigners.
20Pr 20:17 Food gained by fraud is sweet to a man, but afterwards his mouth is full of gravel.
20Pr 20:18 Finalize plans through counsel, and wage war with sound guidance.
20Pr 20:19 The one who reveals secrets is a constant gossip; avoid someone with a big mouth.
20Pr 20:20 Whoever curses his father or mother-- his lamp will go out in deep darkness.
20Pr 20:21 An inheritance gained prematurely will not be blessed ultimately.
20Pr 20:22 Don't say, "I will avenge this evil!" Wait on the LORD, and He will rescue you.
20Pr 20:23 Differing weights are detestable to the LORD, and dishonest scales are unfair.
20Pr 20:24 A man's steps are determined by the LORD, so how can anyone understand his own way?
20Pr 20:25 It is a trap for anyone to dedicate something rashly and later to reconsider his vows.
20Pr 20:26 A wise king separates out the wicked and drives the threshing wheel over them.
20Pr 20:27 A person's breath is the lamp of the LORD, searching the innermost parts.
20Pr 20:28 Loyalty and faithfulness deliver a king; through loyalty he maintains his throne.
20Pr 20:29 The glory of young men is their strength, and the splendor of old men is gray hair.
20Pr 20:30 Lashes and wounds purge away evil, and beatings cleanse the innermost parts.
20Pr 21:1 A king's heart is a water channel in the LORD's hand: He directs it wherever He chooses.
20Pr 21:2 All the ways of a man seem right to him, but the LORD evaluates the motives.
20Pr 21:3 Doing what is righteous and just is more acceptable to the LORD than sacrifice.
20Pr 21:4 The lamp that guides the wicked-- haughty eyes and an arrogant heart-- is sin.
20Pr 21:5 The plans of the diligent certainly lead to profit, but anyone who is reckless only becomes poor.
20Pr 21:6 Making a fortune through a lying tongue is a vanishing mist, a pursuit of death.
20Pr 21:7 The violence of the wicked sweeps them away because they refuse to act justly.
20Pr 21:8 A guilty man's conduct is crooked, but the behavior of the innocent is upright.
20Pr 21:9 Better to live on the corner of a roof than to share a house with a nagging wife.
20Pr 21:10 A wicked person desires evil; he has no consideration for his neighbor.
20Pr 21:11 When a mocker is punished, the inexperienced become wiser; when one teaches a wise man, he acquires knowledge.
20Pr 21:12 The Righteous One considers the house of the wicked; He brings the wicked to ruin.
20Pr 21:13 The one who shuts his ears to the cry of the poor will himself also call out and not be answered.
20Pr 21:14 A secret gift soothes anger, and a covert bribe, fierce rage.
20Pr 21:15 Justice executed is a joy to the righteous but a terror to those who practice iniquity.
20Pr 21:16 The man who strays from the way of wisdom will come to rest in the assembly of the departed spirits.
20Pr 21:17 The one who loves pleasure will become a poor man; whoever loves wine and oil will not get rich.
20Pr 21:18 The wicked are a ransom for the righteous, and the treacherous, for the upright.
20Pr 21:19 Better to live in a wilderness than with a nagging and hot-tempered wife.
20Pr 21:20 Precious treasure and oil are in the dwelling of the wise, but a foolish man consumes them.
20Pr 21:21 The one who pursues righteousness and faithful love will find life, righteousness, and honor.
20Pr 21:22 The wise conquer a city of warriors and bring down its mighty fortress.
20Pr 21:23 The one who guards his mouth and tongue keeps himself out of trouble.
20Pr 21:24 The proud and arrogant person, named "Mocker," acts with excessive pride.
20Pr 21:25 A slacker's craving will kill him because his hands refuse to work.
20Pr 21:26 He is filled with craving all day long, but the righteous give and don't hold back.
20Pr 21:27 The sacrifice of a wicked person is detestable-- how much more so when he brings it with ulterior motives!
20Pr 21:28 A lying witness will perish, but the one who listens will speak successfully.
20Pr 21:29 A wicked man puts on a bold face, but the upright man considers his way.
20Pr 21:30 No wisdom, no understanding, and no counsel [will prevail] against the LORD.
20Pr 21:31 A horse is prepared for the day of battle, but victory comes from the LORD.
20Pr 22:1 A good name is to be chosen over great wealth; favor is better than silver and gold.
20Pr 22:2 The rich and the poor have this in common: the LORD made them both.
20Pr 22:3 A sensible person sees danger and takes cover, but the inexperienced keep going and are punished.
20Pr 22:4 The result of humility is fear of the LORD, along with wealth, honor, and life.
20Pr 22:5 There are thorns and snares on the path of the crooked; the one who guards himself stays far from them.
20Pr 22:6 Teach a youth about the way he should go; even when he is old he will not depart from it.
20Pr 22:7 The rich rule over the poor, and the borrower is a slave to the lender.
20Pr 22:8 The one who sows injustice will reap disaster, and the rod of his fury will be destroyed.
20Pr 22:9 A generous person will be blessed, for he shares his food with the poor.
20Pr 22:10 Drive out a mocker, and conflict goes too; then lawsuits and dishonor will cease.
20Pr 22:11 The one who loves a pure heart and gracious lips-- the king is his friend.
20Pr 22:12 The LORD's eyes keep watch over knowledge, but He overthrows the words of the treacherous.
20Pr 22:13 The slacker says, "There's a lion outside! I'll be killed in the streets!"
20Pr 22:14 The mouth of the forbidden woman is a deep pit; a man cursed by the LORD will fall into it.
20Pr 22:15 Foolishness is tangled up in the heart of a youth; the rod of discipline will drive it away from him.
20Pr 22:16 Oppressing the poor to enrich oneself, and giving to the rich-- both lead only to poverty.
20Pr 22:17 Listen closely, pay attention to the words of the wise, and apply your mind to my knowledge.
20Pr 22:18 For it is pleasing if you keep them within you and if they are constantly on your lips.
20Pr 22:19 I have instructed you today-- even you-- so that your confidence may be in the LORD.
20Pr 22:20 Haven't I written for you thirty sayings about counsel and knowledge,
20Pr 22:21 in order to teach you true and reliable words, so that you may give a dependable report to those who sent you?
20Pr 22:22 Don't rob a poor man because he is poor, and don't crush the oppressed at the gate,
20Pr 22:23 for the LORD will take up their case and will plunder those who plunder them.
20Pr 22:24 Don't make friends with an angry man, and don't be a companion of a hot-tempered man,
20Pr 22:25 or you will learn his ways and entangle yourself in a snare.
20Pr 22:26 Don't be one of those who enter agreements, who put up security for loans.
20Pr 22:27 If you have no money to pay, even your bed will be taken from under you.
20Pr 22:28 Don't move an ancient property line that your fathers set up.
20Pr 22:29 Do you see a man skilled in his work? He will stand in the presence of kings. He will not stand in the presence of unknown men.
20Pr 23:1 When you sit down to dine with a ruler, consider carefully what is before you,
20Pr 23:2 and stick a knife in your throat if you have a big appetite;
20Pr 23:3 don't desire his choice food, for that food is deceptive.
20Pr 23:4 Don't wear yourself out to get rich; stop giving your attention to it.
20Pr 23:5 As soon as your eyes fly to it, it disappears, for it makes wings for itself and flies like an eagle to the sky.
20Pr 23:6 Don't eat a stingy person's bread, and don't desire his choice food,
20Pr 23:7 for as he thinks within himself, so he is. "Eat and drink," he says to you, but his heart is not with you.
20Pr 23:8 You will vomit the little you've eaten and waste your pleasant words.
20Pr 23:9 Don't speak to a fool, for he will despise the insight of your words.
20Pr 23:10 Don't move an ancient property line, and don't encroach on the fields of the fatherless,
20Pr 23:11 for their Redeemer is strong, and He will take up their case against you.
20Pr 23:12 Apply yourself to instruction and listen to words of knowledge.
20Pr 23:13 Don't withhold correction from a youth; if you beat him with a rod, he will not die.
20Pr 23:14 Strike him with a rod, and you will rescue his life from Sheol.
20Pr 23:15 My son, if your heart is wise, my heart will indeed rejoice.
20Pr 23:16 My innermost being will cheer when your lips say what is right.
20Pr 23:17 Don't be jealous of sinners; instead, always fear the LORD.
20Pr 23:18 For then you will have a future, and your hope will never fade.
20Pr 23:19 Listen, my son, and be wise; keep your mind on the right course.
20Pr 23:20 Don't associate with those who drink too much wine, or with those who gorge themselves on meat.
20Pr 23:21 For the drunkard and the glutton will become poor, and grogginess will clothe [them] in rags.
20Pr 23:22 Listen to your father who gave you life, and don't despise your mother when she is old.
20Pr 23:23 Buy-- and do not sell-- truth, wisdom, instruction, and understanding.
20Pr 23:24 The father of a righteous son will rejoice greatly, and one who fathers a wise son will delight in him.
20Pr 23:25 Let your father and mother have joy, and let her who gave birth to you rejoice.
20Pr 23:26 My son, give me your heart, and let your eyes observe my ways.
20Pr 23:27 For a prostitute is a deep pit, and a forbidden woman is a narrow well;
20Pr 23:28 indeed, she sets an ambush like a robber and increases those among men who are unfaithful.
20Pr 23:29 Who has woe? Who has sorrow? Who has conflicts? Who has complaints? Who has wounds for no reason? Who has red eyes?
20Pr 23:30 Those who linger over wine, those who go looking for mixed wine.
20Pr 23:31 Don't gaze at wine when it is red, when it gleams in the cup and goes down smoothly.
20Pr 23:32 In the end it bites like a snake and stings like a viper.
20Pr 23:33 Your eyes will see strange things, and you will say absurd things.
20Pr 23:34 You'll be like someone sleeping out at sea or lying down on the top of a ship's mast.
20Pr 23:35 "They struck me, but I feel no pain! They beat me, but I didn't know it! When will I wake up? I'll look for another [drink]."
20Pr 24:1 Don't envy evil men or desire to be with them,
20Pr 24:2 for their hearts plan violence, and their words stir up trouble.
20Pr 24:3 A house is built by wisdom, and it is established by understanding;
20Pr 24:4 by knowledge the rooms are filled with every precious and beautiful treasure.
20Pr 24:5 A wise warrior is better than a strong one, and a man of knowledge than one of strength;
20Pr 24:6 for you should wage war with sound guidance-- victory comes with many counselors.
20Pr 24:7 Wisdom is inaccessible to a fool; he does not open his mouth at the gate.
20Pr 24:8 The one who plots evil will be called a schemer.
20Pr 24:9 A foolish scheme is sin, and a mocker is detestable to people.
20Pr 24:10 If you do nothing in a difficult time, your strength is limited.
20Pr 24:11 Rescue those being taken off to death, and save those stumbling toward slaughter.
20Pr 24:12 If you say, "But we didn't know about this," won't He who weighs hearts consider it? Won't He who protects your life know? Won't He repay a person according to his work?
20Pr 24:13 Eat honey, my son, for it is good, and the honeycomb is sweet to your palate;
20Pr 24:14 realize that wisdom is the same for you. If you find it, you will have a future, and your hope will never fade.
20Pr 24:15 Don't set an ambush, wicked man, at the camp of the righteous man; don't destroy his dwelling.
20Pr 24:16 Though a righteous man falls seven times, he will get up, but the wicked will stumble into ruin.
20Pr 24:17 Don't gloat when your enemy falls, and don't let your heart rejoice when he stumbles,
20Pr 24:18 or the LORD will see, be displeased, and turn His wrath away from him.
20Pr 24:19 Don't worry because of evildoers, and don't envy the wicked.
20Pr 24:20 For the evil have no future; the lamp of the wicked will be put out.
20Pr 24:21 My son, fear the LORD, as well as the king, and don't associate with rebels,
20Pr 24:22 for their destruction will come suddenly; who knows what disaster these two can bring?
20Pr 24:23 These [sayings] also belong to the wise: It is not good to show partiality in judgment.
20Pr 24:24 Whoever says to the guilty, "You are innocent"-- people will curse him, and tribes will denounce him;
20Pr 24:25 but it will go well with those who convict the guilty, and a generous blessing will come to them.
20Pr 24:26 He who gives an honest answer gives a kiss on the lips.
20Pr 24:27 Complete your outdoor work, and prepare your field; afterwards, build your house.
20Pr 24:28 Don't testify against your neighbor without cause. Don't deceive with your lips.
20Pr 24:29 Don't say, "I'll do to him what he did to me; I'll repay the man for what he has done."
20Pr 24:30 I went by the field of a slacker and by the vineyard of a man lacking sense.
20Pr 24:31 Thistles had come up everywhere, weeds covered the ground, and the stone wall was ruined.
20Pr 24:32 I saw, and took it to heart; I looked, and received instruction:
20Pr 24:33 a little sleep, a little slumber, a little folding of the arms to rest,
20Pr 24:34 and your poverty will come like a robber, your need, like a bandit.
20Pr 25:1 These too are proverbs of Solomon, which the men of Hezekiah, king of Judah, copied.
20Pr 25:2 It is the glory of God to conceal a matter and the glory of kings to investigate a matter.
20Pr 25:3 As the heaven is high and the earth is deep, so the hearts of kings cannot be investigated.
20Pr 25:4 Remove impurities from silver, and a vessel will be produced for a silversmith.
20Pr 25:5 Remove the wicked from the king's presence, and his throne will be established in righteousness.
20Pr 25:6 Don't brag about yourself before the king, and don't stand in the place of the great;
20Pr 25:7 for it is better for him to say to you, "Come up here!" than to demote you in plain view of a noble.
20Pr 25:8 Don't take a matter to court hastily. Otherwise, what will you do afterwards if your opponent humiliates you?
20Pr 25:9 Make your case with your opponent without revealing another's secret;
20Pr 25:10 otherwise, the one who hears will disgrace you, and you'll never live it down.
20Pr 25:11 A word spoken at the right time is like golden apples on a silver tray.
20Pr 25:12 A wise correction to a receptive ear is like a gold ring or an ornament of gold.
20Pr 25:13 To those who send him, a trustworthy messenger is like the coolness of snow on a harvest day; he refreshes the life of his masters.
20Pr 25:14 The man who boasts about a gift that does not exist is like clouds and wind without rain.
20Pr 25:15 A ruler can be persuaded through patience, and a gentle tongue can break a bone.
20Pr 25:16 If you find honey, eat only what you need; otherwise, you'll get sick from it and vomit.
20Pr 25:17 Seldom set foot in your neighbor's house; otherwise, he'll get sick of you and hate you.
20Pr 25:18 A man giving false testimony against his neighbor is like a club, a sword, or a sharp arrow.
20Pr 25:19 Trusting an unreliable person in a time of trouble is like a rotten tooth or a faltering foot.
20Pr 25:20 Singing songs to a troubled heart is like taking off clothing on a cold day, or like [pouring] vinegar on soda.
20Pr 25:21 If your enemy is hungry, give him food to eat, and if he is thirsty, give him water to drink;
20Pr 25:22 for you will heap coals on his head, and the LORD will reward you.
20Pr 25:23 The north wind produces rain, and a backbiting tongue, angry looks.
20Pr 25:24 Better to live on the corner of a roof than in a house shared with a nagging wife.
20Pr 25:25 Good news from a distant land is like cold water to a parched throat.
20Pr 25:26 A righteous person who yields to the wicked is like a muddied spring or a polluted well.
20Pr 25:27 It is not good to eat too much honey, or to seek glory after glory.
20Pr 25:28 A man who does not control his temper is like a city whose wall is broken down.
20Pr 26:1 Like snow in summer and rain at harvest, honor is inappropriate for a fool.
20Pr 26:2 Like a flitting sparrow or a fluttering swallow, an undeserved curse goes nowhere.
20Pr 26:3 A whip for the horse, a bridle for the donkey, and a rod for the backs of fools.
20Pr 26:4 Don't answer a fool according to his foolishness, or you'll be like him yourself.
20Pr 26:5 Answer a fool according to his foolishness, or he'll become wise in his own eyes.
20Pr 26:6 The one who sends a message by a fool's hand cuts off his own feet and drinks violence.
20Pr 26:7 A proverb in the mouth of a fool is like lame legs that hang limp.
20Pr 26:8 Giving honor to a fool is like binding a stone in a sling.
20Pr 26:9 A proverb in the mouth of a fool is like a stick with thorns, brandished by the hand of a drunkard.
20Pr 26:10 The one who hires a fool, or who hires those passing by, is like an archer who wounds everyone.
20Pr 26:11 As a dog returns to its vomit, so a fool repeats his foolishness.
20Pr 26:12 Do you see a man who is wise in his own eyes? There is more hope for a fool than for him.
20Pr 26:13 The slacker says, "There's a lion in the road-- a lion in the public square!"
20Pr 26:14 A door turns on its hinge, and a slacker, on his bed.
20Pr 26:15 The slacker buries his hand in the bowl; he is too weary to bring it to his mouth.
20Pr 26:16 In his own eyes, a slacker is wiser than seven men who can answer sensibly.
20Pr 26:17 A passerby who meddles in a quarrel that's not his is like one who grabs a dog by the ears.
20Pr 26:18 Like a madman who throws flaming darts and deadly arrows,
20Pr 26:19 so is the man who deceives his neighbor and says, "I was only joking!"
20Pr 26:20 Without wood, fire goes out; without a gossip, conflict dies down.
20Pr 26:21 As charcoal for embers and wood for fire, so is a quarrelsome man for kindling strife.
20Pr 26:22 A gossip's words are like choice food that goes down to one's innermost being.
20Pr 26:23 Smooth lips with an evil heart are like glaze on an earthen vessel.
20Pr 26:24 A hateful person disguises himself with his speech and harbors deceit within.
20Pr 26:25 When he speaks graciously, don't believe him, for there are seven abominations in his heart.
20Pr 26:26 Though his hatred is concealed by deception, his evil will be revealed in the assembly.
20Pr 26:27 The one who digs a pit will fall into it, and whoever rolls a stone-- it will come back on him.
20Pr 26:28 A lying tongue hates those it crushes, and a flattering mouth causes ruin.
20Pr 27:1 Don't boast about tomorrow, for you don't know what a day might bring.
20Pr 27:2 Let another praise you, and not your own mouth-- a stranger, and not your own lips.
20Pr 27:3 A stone is heavy and sand, a burden, but aggravation from a fool outweighs them both.
20Pr 27:4 Fury is cruel, and anger is a flood, but who can withstand jealousy?
20Pr 27:5 Better an open reprimand than concealed love.
20Pr 27:6 The wounds of a friend are trustworthy, but the kisses of an enemy are excessive.
20Pr 27:7 A person who is full tramples on a honeycomb, but to a hungry person, any bitter thing is sweet.
20Pr 27:8 A man wandering from his home is like a bird wandering from its nest.
20Pr 27:9 Oil and incense bring joy to the heart, and the sweetness of a friend is better than self-counsel.
20Pr 27:10 Don't abandon your friend or your father's friend, and don't go to your brother's house in your time of calamity; better a neighbor nearby than a brother far away.
20Pr 27:11 Be wise, my son, and bring my heart joy, so that I can answer anyone who taunts me.
20Pr 27:12 The sensible see danger and take cover; the foolish keep going and are punished.
20Pr 27:13 Take his garment, for he has put up security for a stranger; get collateral if it is for foreigners.
20Pr 27:14 If one blesses his neighbor with a loud voice early in the morning, it will be counted as a curse to him.
20Pr 27:15 An endless dripping on a rainy day and a nagging wife are alike.
20Pr 27:16 The one who controls her controls the wind and grasps oil with his right hand.
20Pr 27:17 Iron sharpens iron, and one man sharpens another.
20Pr 27:18 Whoever tends a fig tree will eat its fruit, and whoever looks after his master will be honored.
20Pr 27:19 As the water reflects the face, so the heart reflects the person.
20Pr 27:20 Sheol and Abaddon are never satisfied, and people's eyes are never satisfied.
20Pr 27:21 Silver is [tested] in a crucible, gold in a smelter, and a man, by the praise he receives.
20Pr 27:22 Though you grind a fool in a mortar with a pestle along with grain, you will not separate his foolishness from him.
20Pr 27:23 Know well the condition of your flock, and pay attention to your herds,
20Pr 27:24 for wealth is not forever; not even a crown lasts for all time.
20Pr 27:25 When hay is removed and new growth appears and the grain from the hills is gathered in,
20Pr 27:26 lambs will provide your clothing, and goats, the price of a field;
20Pr 27:27 there will be enough goat's milk for your food-- food for your household and nourishment for your servants.
20Pr 28:1 The wicked flee when no one is pursuing [them], but the righteous are as bold as a lion.
20Pr 28:2 When a land is in rebellion, it has many rulers, but with a discerning and knowledgeable person, it endures.
20Pr 28:3 A destitute leader who oppresses the poor is like a driving rain that leaves no food.
20Pr 28:4 Those who reject the law praise the wicked, but those who keep the law battle against them.
20Pr 28:5 Evil men do not understand justice, but those who seek the LORD understand everything.
20Pr 28:6 Better a poor man who lives with integrity than a rich man who distorts right and wrong.
20Pr 28:7 A discerning son keeps the law, but a companion of gluttons humiliates his father.
20Pr 28:8 Whoever increases his wealth through excessive interest collects it for one who is kind to the poor.
20Pr 28:9 Anyone who turns his ear away from hearing the law-- even his prayer is detestable.
20Pr 28:10 The one who leads the upright into an evil way will fall into his own pit, but the blameless will inherit what is good.
20Pr 28:11 A rich man is wise in his own eyes, but a poor man who has discernment sees through him.
20Pr 28:12 When the righteous triumph, there is great rejoicing, but when the wicked come to power, people hide themselves.
20Pr 28:13 The one who conceals his sins will not prosper, but whoever confesses and renounces them will find mercy.
20Pr 28:14 Happy is the one who is always reverent, but one who hardens his heart falls into trouble.
20Pr 28:15 A wicked ruler over a helpless people is like a roaring lion or a charging bear.
20Pr 28:16 A leader who lacks understanding is very oppressive, but one who hates unjust gain prolongs his life.
20Pr 28:17 A man burdened by bloodguilt will be a fugitive until death. Let no one help him.
20Pr 28:18 The one who lives with integrity will be helped, but one who distorts right and wrong will suddenly fall.
20Pr 28:19 The one who works his land will have plenty of food, but whoever chases fantasies will have his fill of poverty.
20Pr 28:20 A faithful man will have many blessings, but one in a hurry to get rich will not go unpunished.
20Pr 28:21 It is not good to show partiality-- yet a man may sin for a piece of bread.
20Pr 28:22 A greedy man is in a hurry for wealth; he doesn't know that poverty will come to him.
20Pr 28:23 One who rebukes a person will later find more favor than one who flatters with his tongue.
20Pr 28:24 The one who robs his father or mother and says, "That's no sin," is a companion to a man who destroys.
20Pr 28:25 A greedy person provokes conflict, but whoever trusts in the LORD will prosper.
20Pr 28:26 The one who trusts in himself is a fool, but one who walks in wisdom will be safe.
20Pr 28:27 The one who gives to the poor will not be in need, but one who turns his eyes away will receive many curses.
20Pr 28:28 When the wicked come to power, people hide, but when they are destroyed, the righteous flourish.
20Pr 29:1 One who becomes stiff-necked, after many reprimands will be broken suddenly-- and without a remedy.
20Pr 29:2 When the righteous flourish, the people rejoice, but when the wicked rule, people groan.
20Pr 29:3 A man who loves wisdom brings joy to his father, but one who consorts with prostitutes destroys his wealth.
20Pr 29:4 By justice a king brings stability to a land, but a man [who demands] "contributions" demolishes it.
20Pr 29:5 A man who flatters his neighbor spreads a net for his feet.
20Pr 29:6 An evil man is caught by sin, but the righteous one sings and rejoices.
20Pr 29:7 The righteous person knows the rights of the poor, but the wicked one does not understand these concerns.
20Pr 29:8 Mockers inflame a city, but the wise turn away anger.
20Pr 29:9 If a wise man goes to court with a fool, there will be ranting and raving but no resolution.
20Pr 29:10 Bloodthirsty men hate an honest person, but the upright care about him.
20Pr 29:11 A fool gives full vent to his anger, but a wise man holds it in check.
20Pr 29:12 If a ruler listens to lies, all his servants will be wicked.
20Pr 29:13 The poor and the oppressor have this in common: the LORD gives light to the eyes of both.
20Pr 29:14 A king who judges the poor with fairness-- his throne will be established forever.
20Pr 29:15 A rod of correction imparts wisdom, but a youth left to himself is a disgrace to his mother.
20Pr 29:16 When the wicked increase, rebellion increases, but the righteous will see their downfall.
20Pr 29:17 Discipline your son, and he will give you comfort; he will also give you delight.
20Pr 29:18 Without revelation people run wild, but one who keeps the law will be happy.
20Pr 29:19 A servant cannot be disciplined by words; though he understands, he doesn't respond.
20Pr 29:20 Do you see a man who speaks too soon? There is more hope for a fool than for him.
20Pr 29:21 A slave pampered from his youth will become arrogant later on.
20Pr 29:22 An angry man stirs up conflict, and a hot-tempered man increases rebellion.
20Pr 29:23 A person's pride will humble him, but a humble spirit will gain honor.
20Pr 29:24 To be a thief's partner is to hate oneself; he hears the curse but will not testify.
20Pr 29:25 The fear of man is a snare, but the one who trusts in the LORD is protected.
20Pr 29:26 Many seek a ruler's favor, but a man receives justice from the LORD.
20Pr 29:27 An unjust man is detestable to the righteous, and one whose way is upright is detestable to the wicked.
20Pr 30:1 The words of Agur son of Jakeh. The oracle. The man's oration to Ithiel, to Ithiel and Ucal:
20Pr 30:2 I am the least intelligent of men, and I lack man's ability to understand.
20Pr 30:3 I have not gained wisdom, and I have no knowledge of the Holy One.
20Pr 30:4 Who has gone up to heaven and come down? Who has gathered the wind in His hands? Who has bound up the waters in a cloak? Who has established all the ends of the earth? What is His name, and what is the name of His Son-- if you know?
20Pr 30:5 Every word of God is pure; He is a shield to those who take refuge in Him.
20Pr 30:6 Don't add to His words, or He will rebuke you, and you will be proved a liar.
20Pr 30:7 Two things I ask of You; don't deny them to me before I die:
20Pr 30:8 Keep falsehood and deceitful words far from me. Give me neither poverty nor wealth; feed me with the food I need.
20Pr 30:9 Otherwise, I might have too much and deny You, saying, "Who is the LORD?" or I might have nothing and steal, profaning the name of my God.
20Pr 30:10 Don't slander a servant to his master, or he will curse you, and you will become guilty.
20Pr 30:11 There is a generation that curses its father and does not bless its mother.
20Pr 30:12 There is a generation that is pure in its own eyes, yet is not washed from its filth.
20Pr 30:13 There is a generation-- how haughty its eyes and pretentious its looks.
20Pr 30:14 There is a generation whose teeth are swords, whose fangs are knives, devouring the oppressed from the land and the needy from among mankind.
20Pr 30:15 The leech has two daughters: Give, Give. Three things are never satisfied; four never say, "Enough!":
20Pr 30:16 Sheol; a barren womb; earth, which is never satisfied with water; and fire, which never says, "Enough!"
20Pr 30:17 As for the eye that ridicules a father and despises obedience to a mother, may ravens of the valley pluck it out and young vultures eat it.
20Pr 30:18 Three things are beyond me; four I can't understand:
20Pr 30:19 the way of an eagle in the sky, the way of a snake on a rock, the way of a ship at sea, and the way of a man with a young woman.
20Pr 30:20 This is the way of an adulteress: she eats and wipes her mouth and says, "I've done nothing wrong."
20Pr 30:21 The earth trembles under three things; it cannot bear up under four:
20Pr 30:22 a servant when he becomes king, a fool when he is stuffed with food,
20Pr 30:23 an unloved woman when she marries, and a serving girl when she ousts her lady.
20Pr 30:24 Four things on earth are small, yet they are extremely wise:
20Pr 30:25 the ants are not a strong people, yet they store up their food in the summer;
20Pr 30:26 hyraxes are not a mighty people, yet they make their homes in the cliffs;
20Pr 30:27 locusts have no king, yet all of them march in ranks;
20Pr 30:28 a lizard can be caught in your hands, yet it lives in kings' palaces.
20Pr 30:29 Three things are stately in their stride, even four are stately in their walk:
20Pr 30:30 a lion, which is mightiest among beasts and doesn't retreat before anything,
20Pr 30:31 a strutting rooster, a goat, and a king at the head of his army.
20Pr 30:32 If you have been foolish by exalting yourself, or if you've been scheming, put your hand over your mouth.
20Pr 30:33 For the churning of milk produces butter, and twisting a nose draws blood, and stirring up anger produces strife.
20Pr 31:1 The words of King Lemuel, an oracle that his mother taught him:
20Pr 31:2 What [should I say], my son? What, son of my womb? What, son of my vows?
20Pr 31:3 Don't spend your energy on women or your efforts on those who destroy kings.
20Pr 31:4 It is not for kings, Lemuel, it is not for kings to drink wine or for rulers [to desire] beer.
20Pr 31:5 Otherwise, they will drink, forget what is decreed, and pervert justice for all the oppressed.
20Pr 31:6 Give beer to one who is dying, and wine to one whose life is bitter.
20Pr 31:7 Let him drink so that he can forget his poverty and remember his trouble no more.
20Pr 31:8 Speak up for those who have no voice, for the justice of all who are dispossessed.
20Pr 31:9 Speak up, judge righteously, and defend the cause of the oppressed and needy.
20Pr 31:10 Who can find a capable wife? She is far more precious than jewels.
20Pr 31:11 The heart of her husband trusts in her, and he will not lack anything good.
20Pr 31:12 She rewards him with good, not evil, all the days of her life.
20Pr 31:13 She selects wool and flax and works with willing hands.
20Pr 31:14 She is like the merchant ships, bringing her food from far away.
20Pr 31:15 She rises while it is still night and provides food for her household and portions for her servants.
20Pr 31:16 She evaluates a field and buys it; she plants a vineyard with her earnings.
20Pr 31:17 She draws on her strength and reveals that her arms are strong.
20Pr 31:18 She sees that her profits are good, and her lamp never goes out at night.
20Pr 31:19 She extends her hands to the spinning staff, and her hands hold the spindle.
20Pr 31:20 Her hands reach out to the poor, and she extends her hands to the needy.
20Pr 31:21 She is not afraid for her household when it snows, for all in her household are doubly clothed.
20Pr 31:22 She makes her own bed coverings; her clothing is fine linen and purple.
20Pr 31:23 Her husband is known at the city gates, where he sits among the elders of the land.
20Pr 31:24 She makes and sells linen garments; she delivers belts to the merchants.
20Pr 31:25 Strength and honor are her clothing, and she can laugh at the time to come.
20Pr 31:26 She opens her mouth with wisdom, and loving instruction is on her tongue.
20Pr 31:27 She watches over the activities of her household and is never idle.
20Pr 31:28 Her sons rise up and call her blessed. Her husband also praises her:
20Pr 31:29 "Many women are capable, but you surpass them all!"
20Pr 31:30 Charm is deceptive and beauty is fleeting, but a woman who fears the LORD will be praised.
20Pr 31:31 Give her the reward of her labor, and let her works praise her at the city gates.
