22Sg 1:1 Solomon's Finest Song
22Sg 1:2 Oh, that he would kiss me with the kisses of his mouth! For your love is more delightful than wine.
22Sg 1:3 The fragrance of your perfume is intoxicating; your name is perfume poured out. No wonder young women adore you.
22Sg 1:4 Take me with you-- let us hurry. Oh, that the king would bring me to his chambers. We will rejoice and be glad for you; we will praise your love more than wine. It is only right that they adore you.
22Sg 1:5 Daughters of Jerusalem, I am dark like the tents of Kedar, yet lovely like the curtains of Solomon.
22Sg 1:6 Do not stare at me because I am dark, for the sun has gazed on me. My mother's sons were angry with me; they made me a keeper of the vineyards. I have not kept my own vineyard.
22Sg 1:7 Tell me, you, the one I love: Where do you pasture your sheep? Where do you let them rest at noon? Why should I be like one who veils herself beside the flocks of your companions?
22Sg 1:8 If you do not know, most beautiful of women, follow the tracks of the flock, and pasture your young goats near the shepherds' tents.
22Sg 1:9 I compare you, my darling, to a mare among Pharaoh's chariots.
22Sg 1:10 Your cheeks are beautiful with jewelry, your neck with its necklace.
22Sg 1:11 We will make gold jewelry for you, accented with silver.
22Sg 1:12 While the king is on his couch, my perfume releases its fragrance.
22Sg 1:13 My love is a sachet of myrrh to me, spending the night between my breasts.
22Sg 1:14 My love is a cluster of henna blossoms to me, in the vineyards of En-gedi.
22Sg 1:15 How beautiful you are, my darling. How very beautiful! Your eyes are doves.
22Sg 1:16 How handsome you are, my love. How delightful! Our bed is lush with foliage;
22Sg 1:17 the beams of our house are cedars, and our rafters are cypresses.
22Sg 2:1 I am a rose of Sharon, a lily of the valleys.
22Sg 2:2 Like a lily among thorns, so is my darling among the young women.
22Sg 2:3 Like an apricot tree among the trees of the forest, so is my love among the young men. I delight to sit in his shade, and his fruit is sweet to my taste.
22Sg 2:4 He brought me to the banquet hall, and he looked on me with love.
22Sg 2:5 Sustain me with raisins; refresh me with apricots, for I am lovesick.
22Sg 2:6 His left hand is under my head, and his right hand embraces me.
22Sg 2:7 Young women of Jerusalem, I charge you, by the gazelles and the wild does of the field: do not stir up or awaken love until the appropriate time.
22Sg 2:8 Listen! My love [is approaching]. Look! Here he comes, leaping over the mountains, bounding over the hills.
22Sg 2:9 My love is like a gazelle or a young stag. Look, he is standing behind our wall, gazing through the windows, peering through the lattice.
22Sg 2:10 My love calls to me: Arise, my darling. Come away, my beautiful one.
22Sg 2:11 For now the winter is past; the rain has ended and gone away.
22Sg 2:12 The blossoms appear in the countryside. The time of singing has come, and the turtledove's cooing is heard in our land.
22Sg 2:13 The fig tree ripens its figs; the blossoming vines give off their fragrance. Arise, my darling. Come away, my beautiful one.
22Sg 2:14 My dove, in the clefts of the rock, in the crevices of the cliff, let me see your face, let me hear your voice; for your voice is sweet, and your face is lovely.
22Sg 2:15 Catch the foxes for us-- the little foxes that ruin the vineyards-- for our vineyards are in bloom.
22Sg 2:16 My love is mine and I am his; he feeds among the lilies.
22Sg 2:17 Before the day breaks and the shadows flee, turn [to me], my love, and be like a gazelle or a young stag on the divided mountains.
22Sg 3:1 In my bed at night I sought the one I love; I sought him, but did not find him.
22Sg 3:2 I will arise now and go about the city, through the streets and the plazas. I will seek the one I love. I sought him, but did not find him.
22Sg 3:3 The guards who go about the city found me. "Have you seen the one I love?" [I asked them].
22Sg 3:4 I had just passed them when I found the one I love. I held on to him and would not let him go until I brought him to my mother's house-- to the chamber of the one who conceived me.
22Sg 3:5 Young women of Jerusalem, I charge you, by the gazelles and the wild does of the field: do not stir up or awaken love until the appropriate time.
22Sg 3:6 What is this coming up from the wilderness like columns of smoke, scented with myrrh and frankincense from every fragrant powder of the merchant?
22Sg 3:7 It is Solomon's royal litter surrounded by 60 warriors from the mighty of Israel.
22Sg 3:8 All of them are skilled with swords and trained in warfare. Each has his sword at his side [to guard] against the terror of the night.
22Sg 3:9 King Solomon made a sedan chair for himself with wood from Lebanon.
22Sg 3:10 He made its posts of silver, its back of gold, and its seat of purple. Its interior is inlaid with love by the young women of Jerusalem.
22Sg 3:11 Come out, young women of Zion, and gaze at King Solomon, wearing the crown his mother placed on him the day of his wedding-- the day of his heart's rejoicing.
22Sg 4:1 How beautiful you are, my darling. How very beautiful! Behind your veil, your eyes are doves. Your hair is like a flock of goats streaming down Mount Gilead.
22Sg 4:2 Your teeth are like a flock of newly shorn [sheep] coming up from washing, each one having a twin, and not one missing.
22Sg 4:3 Your lips are like a scarlet cord, and your mouth is lovely. Behind your veil, your brow is like a slice of pomegranate.
22Sg 4:4 Your neck is like the tower of David, constructed in layers. A thousand bucklers are hung on it-- all of them shields of warriors.
22Sg 4:5 Your breasts are like two fawns, twins of a gazelle, that feed among the lilies.
22Sg 4:6 Before the day breaks and the shadows flee, I will make my way to the mountain of myrrh and the hill of frankincense.
22Sg 4:7 You are absolutely beautiful, my darling, with no imperfection in you.
22Sg 4:8 Come with me from Lebanon, my bride-- with me from Lebanon! Descend from the peak of Amana, from the summit of Senir and Hermon, from the dens of the lions, from the mountains of the leopards.
22Sg 4:9 You have captured my heart, my sister, my bride. You have captured my heart with one glance of your eyes, with one jewel of your necklace.
22Sg 4:10 How delightful your love is, my sister, my bride. Your love is much better than wine, and the fragrance of your perfume than any balsam.
22Sg 4:11 Your lips drip [sweetness like] the honeycomb, my bride. Honey and milk are under your tongue. The fragrance of your garments is like the fragrance of Lebanon.
22Sg 4:12 My sister, my bride, [you are] a locked garden-- a locked garden and a sealed spring.
22Sg 4:13 Your branches are a paradise of pomegranates with choicest fruits, henna with nard--
22Sg 4:14 nard and saffron, calamus and cinnamon, with all the trees of frankincense, myrrh and aloes, with all the best spices.
22Sg 4:15 [You are] a garden spring, a well of flowing water streaming from Lebanon.
22Sg 4:16 Awaken, north wind-- come, south wind. Blow on my garden, and spread the fragrance of its spices. Let my love come to his garden and eat its choicest fruits.
22Sg 5:1 I have come to my garden-- my sister, my bride. I gather my myrrh with my spices. I eat my honeycomb with my honey. I drink my wine with my milk. Eat, friends! Drink, be intoxicated with love!
22Sg 5:2 I sleep, but my heart is awake. A sound! My love is knocking! Open to me, my sister, my darling, my dove, my perfect one. For my head is drenched with dew, my hair with droplets of the night.
22Sg 5:3 I have taken off my clothing. How can I put it back on? I have washed my feet. How can I get them dirty?
22Sg 5:4 My love thrust his hand through the opening, and my feelings were stirred for him.
22Sg 5:5 I rose to open for my love. My hands dripped with myrrh, my fingers with flowing myrrh on the handles of the bolt.
22Sg 5:6 I opened to my love, but my love had turned and gone away. I was crushed that he had left. I sought him, but did not find him. I called him, but he did not answer.
22Sg 5:7 The guards who go about the city found me. They beat and wounded me; they took my cloak from me-- the guardians of the walls.
22Sg 5:8 Young women of Jerusalem, I charge you: if you find my love, tell him that I am lovesick.
22Sg 5:9 What makes the one you love better than another, most beautiful of women? What makes him better than another, that you would give us this charge?
22Sg 5:10 My love is fit and strong, notable among ten thousand.
22Sg 5:11 His head is purest gold. His hair is wavy and black as a raven.
22Sg 5:12 His eyes are like doves beside streams of water, washed in milk and set like jewels.
22Sg 5:13 His cheeks are like beds of spice, towers of perfume. His lips are lilies, dripping with flowing myrrh.
22Sg 5:14 His arms are rods of gold set with topaz. His body is an ivory panel covered with sapphires.
22Sg 5:15 His legs are alabaster pillars set on pedestals of pure gold. His presence is like Lebanon, as majestic as the cedars.
22Sg 5:16 His mouth is sweetness. He is absolutely desirable. This is my love, and this is my friend, young women of Jerusalem.
22Sg 6:1 Where has your love gone, most beautiful of women? Which way has he turned? We will seek him with you.
22Sg 6:2 My love has gone down to his garden, to beds of spice, to feed in the gardens and gather lilies.
22Sg 6:3 I am my love's and my love is mine; he feeds among the lilies.
22Sg 6:4 You are as beautiful as Tirzah, my darling, lovely as Jerusalem, awe-inspiring as an army with banners.
22Sg 6:5 Turn your eyes away from me, for they captivate me. Your hair is like a flock of goats streaming down from Gilead.
22Sg 6:6 Your teeth are like a flock of ewes coming up from washing, each one having a twin, and not one missing.
22Sg 6:7 Behind your veil, your brow is like a slice of pomegranate.
22Sg 6:8 There are 60 queens and 80 concubines and young women without number.
22Sg 6:9 But my dove, my virtuous one, is unique; she is the favorite of her mother, perfect to the one who gave her birth. Women see her and declare her fortunate; queens and concubines also, and they sing her praises:
22Sg 6:10 Who is thiswho shines like the dawn-- as beautiful as the moon, bright as the sun, awe-inspiring as an army with banners?
22Sg 6:11 I came down to the walnut grove to see the blossoms of the valley, to see if the vines were budding and the pomegranates blooming.
22Sg 6:12 Before I knew it, my desire put me [among] the chariots of my noble people.
22Sg 6:13  Come back, come back, Shulammite! Come back, come back, that we may look at you! Why are you looking at the Shulammite, as you [look] at the dance of the two camps?
22Sg 7:1 How beautiful are your sandaled feet, princess! The curves of your thighs are like jewelry, the handiwork of a master.
22Sg 7:2 Your navel is a rounded bowl; it never lacks mixed wine. Your waist is a mound of wheat surrounded by lilies.
22Sg 7:3 Your breasts are like two fawns, twins of a gazelle.
22Sg 7:4 Your neck is like a tower of ivory, your eyes like pools in Heshbon by the gate of Bath-rabbim. Your nose is like the tower of Lebanon looking toward Damascus.
22Sg 7:5 Your head crowns you like Mount Carmel, the hair of your head like purple cloth-- a king could be held captive in your tresses.
22Sg 7:6 How beautiful you are and how pleasant, [my] love, with such delights!
22Sg 7:7 Your stature is like a palm tree; your breasts are clusters [of fruit].
22Sg 7:8 I said, "I will climb the palm tree and take hold of its fruit." May your breasts be like clusters of grapes, and the fragrance of your breath like apricots.
22Sg 7:9 Your mouth is like fine wine-- flowing smoothly for my love gliding past my lips and teeth!
22Sg 7:10 I belong to my love, and his desire is for me.
22Sg 7:11 Come, my love, let's go to the field; let's spend the night among the henna blossoms.
22Sg 7:12 Let's go early to the vineyards; let's see if the vine has budded, if the blossom has opened, if the pomegranates are in bloom. There I will give you my love.
22Sg 7:13 The mandrakes give off a fragrance, and at our doors is every delicacy-- new as well as old. I have treasured them up for you, my love.
22Sg 8:1 If only I could treat you like my brother, one who nursed at my mother's breasts, I would find you in public and kiss you, and no one would scorn me.
22Sg 8:2 I would lead you, I would take you, to the house of my mother who taught me. I would give you spiced wine to drink from my pomegranate juice.
22Sg 8:3 His left hand is under my head, and his right hand embraces me.
22Sg 8:4 Young women of Jerusalem, I charge you: do not stir up or awaken love until the appropriate time.
22Sg 8:5 Who is this coming up from the wilderness, leaning on the one she loves? I awakened you under the apricot tree. There your mother conceived you; there she conceived and gave you birth.
22Sg 8:6 Set me as a seal on your heart, as a seal on your arm. For love is as strong as death; ardent love is as unrelenting as Sheol. Love's flames are fiery flames-- the fiercest of all.
22Sg 8:7 Mighty waters cannot extinguish love; rivers cannot sweep it away. If a man were to give all his wealth for love, it would be utterly scorned.
22Sg 8:8 Our sister is young; she has no breasts. What will we do for our sister on the day she is spoken for?
22Sg 8:9 If she is a wall, we will build a silver parapet on it. If she is a door, we will enclose it with cedar planks.
22Sg 8:10 I am a wall and my breasts like towers. So in his eyes I have become like one who finds peace.
22Sg 8:11 Solomon owned a vineyard in Baal-hamon. He leased the vineyard to tenants. Each was to bring for his fruit 1,000 pieces of silver.
22Sg 8:12 I have my own vineyard. The 1,000 are for you, Solomon, but 200 for those who guard its fruits.
22Sg 8:13 You who dwell in the gardens-- companions are listening for your voice-- let me hear you!
22Sg 8:14 Hurry [to me], my love, and be like a gazelle or a young stag on the mountains of spices.
